OE_upsetting: Inability to buy groceries and basic goods after a day of work.
OE_positive: The gratitude from companies and organizations such as meals and discounts have made me feel appreciated.

OE_upsetting: not being able to work in the same capacity, switched to ICU from OR work. Makes me feel anxious, lack of control
OE_positive: the support of the community and the city has been uplifting

OE_upsetting:
Not having control over whether I could shelter in place or continue to work. Program claimed that we could opt out, but then immediately followed that, by telling us that nobody had opted out yet. 
Lack on control over my own life, because of the repercussions from the residency program. So while on paper one might say, you can opt-out. You can’t actually, not without fear of retribution, or bad evaluations.
OE_positive:
Hearing that the economies and stores might begin to open soon.
Not getting overwhelmed in San Francisco, like wed expected.
Getting a few reading days off from work.
OE_other: I wish it were all over already. I want to shelter in place too, instead of going to work.

He died 24 hours later. I washed, decontaminated, shaved my head, and my family distanced from me for a month. I didn't hold my wife's hand for almost two months.
OE_positive: Worked on research to unerstand role of ACE-2 receptors in COVID-19 infections
OE_other: This pandemic is completely expected and is following a completely predictable worst case situation, the fact that we have a sociopathic, narcicist, as president is making it vastly worse. Donald Trump is increasing the case numbers and mortality secondary to incompetence. It is frustrating that our government is being run by someone who is trying to profit, deflect, and lie his way out of the problem.

OE_upsetting: Difficulty and delays getting medical care that was non-urgent but important to my wellbeing. Felt frustrated and loss of control.
OE_positive: Spending more time outside. Talking to friends more frequently on the phone.

OE_upsetting: Being isolated at work.  I have been working alone at the hospital.
OE_positive: Seeing my high risk patients largely survive--much higher survival rate than I had expected.

OE_upsetting: Feeling at odds over resource allocation for COVID-19 patients. There wasn’t so much disagreement as there was general distress over the event even needing to happen. It’s hard to reconcile the reality of these conversations with social media messages from friends (including health care workers!) who don’t believe what’s happening in areas of the world more affected than where we work.
OE_positive: The sense of solidarity. The amount of appreciation I have for other people.

OE_upsetting: I convinced a patient to go to the hospital with us for medical evaluation after she had two syncopal episodes. She was adamant about not going d to her fears of contracting COVID and dying from it. She went to the ER with us and later I found out the probability she would contract COVID was extremely high and based upon her pre-existing condition will probably die.
OE_positive: The outpouring of support from the public and the nation towards first responders has been extremely uplifting and amazing. We have been receiving letters, cards, and meals sent to us every shift. There is a new appreciation for EMS, that was never there before, and this has provided me and my colleague's encouragement and support during these unprecedented times.

OE_upsetting: my kids not being able to see their grandmother for fear that they will expose her to COVID-19 based on my job.
OE_positive: spending more time with husband and kids
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Unable to find my necessities when at a grocery store.
OE_positive: Everyone has worked as a team to help in this hard situation. We have bonded more in these times because of this.

OE_upsetting: Death in the family, not covid related. I was most concerned about family members traveling and making arrangements for services amidst the pandemic
OE_positive: More time at home rather than an abundance of social obligations

OE_upsetting: A close friend became very ill (with another unknown virus) - and because of covid she was terrified to go to the ED when necessary - and then the support that I could offer was limited following her hospitalization. (Couldn't be there physically to support her).
OE_positive: More connection to my team and more text/friendly banter communication. Also, the opportunity to reconnect with past teachers (dance and yoga) and take classes with them again... at 5am!
OE_other: I am fortunate to work somewhere that is as prepared as anyone could have been - with a very low mortality rate.

OE_upsetting: Working 24/7 on urgent initiatives because there is a fear of layoffs in the near future and we need to get things done while we still have resources, being treated as though I'm not doing enough, and simultaneously being told to be sure to take care of myself and my mental health. It makes me feel frantic and disposable.
OE_positive: Seeing the effect that this is having on wildlife.

OE_upsetting: Anti Asian sentiment due to fear of COVID 19.
OE_positive: Acknowledgement by other non clinical staff

OE_upsetting: I miss seeing and being with others.  At least I am with my family, 6 of us in total.

OE_positive: My family is home all day and we get to enjoy this time with our child.

OE_positive: I am proud of our hospital, our university, and our county for mobilizing so quickly and reducing barriers to continuing our care. I love my staff, my leadership, it has been an incredibly supportive and privileged environment for me to work in during this time.

OE_positive: Office might let me work from home all the time to avoid the 4 hour round trip commute. But we have to get over COVID first.
OE_other: Trying to get government assistance has been horrible. My husband is not working, but my income disqualifies us from some services, like food stamps. Food banks have been helpful. Also mortgage company has not said if they will freeze my mortgage, so worried I will have to pay 6 months at once.

OE_upsetting: Slow rollout of protections for staff and patients in my department, making me feel like we are all a low priority.
OE_positive: Connecting more with parents by phone

OE_upsetting: Being publicly chastised by a superior for bringing up my concerns about how infection might impact sick leave and pay, and having the GME bluntly state residents are not eligible for hazard pay in spite of requesting we reuse ppe.

OE_upsetting: Our US government and Trump not taking ownership of the terribly lacking national government response to COVID. Stop blaming other nations and stop spreading hate. Our government needs to become more empathetic and peaceful and less full of liars and xenophobic bullies and haters.

OE_other: Our national government under Trump is the bane of our American health worker existence - liars, bullies, racists, haters, anti-scientists, and expedient xenophobes who focus solely on making geopolitical wars to divert attention from their own failings, solely focused on winning the November election, to the detriment of the American public.

OE_upsetting: Not personal: seeing disregard for sound science-based information. I feel that the resulting damage is not reversible.
OE_positive: No surge at my hospital. I feel like interventions worked so far.

OE_positive: Hugging my partner in secret between two parked cars

OE_upsetting: None
OE_positive: Gratitude for health and safety

OE_upsetting: At the beginning of the pandemic, one of the patients I would be anesthetizing for a nasal endoscopy (high risk surgery for covid transmission) reported a new “one-time cough” during a telephone appointment with the prepare clinic.  He didn’t have any other symptoms or fever.  The surgeon was okay proceeding with the case, and I brought it up to my manager that I wanted to have full PPE (PAPR or N95) for this case because we did not know the covid status of this newly symptomatic patient. The issue was brought all the way up to the chairs of anesthesia and ENT, and they decided that it was okay to proceed with standard PPE. I was not comfortable with this at all, and asked to be taken off the case. Just a couple of days later, the hospital implemented a policy where staff taking care of any patient undergoing an aerosol generating procedure would have to don full PPE, and I honestly felt cheated/short-changed in that they were completely okay sending staff into a high risk procedure without full protection only a few days prior.
OE_positive: The most positive thing is being surrounded by colleagues who understand my feelings.

OE_upsetting: Cancellation of multiple important work-related meetings that I was looking forward to. I feel as though I have nothing to look forward to, and no control over my work and personal life.
OE_positive: Comparing thoughts and feelings with friends and colleagues. Good to know others feels as I do.

OE_upsetting: My husband’s small business was closed due to shelter in place orders from 3/18 and until at least 5/31 (for now).
OE_positive: The support and encouragement from my supervisor

OE_upsetting: Personally, the most upsetting thing is missing family and friends due to shelter-in-place order. It makes me feel isolated, lonely, bored, frustrated, sad.
OE_positive: I have spent much more time with my daughter due to staying home and losing our child care. If it weren’t for the pandemic, I would never have spent this much time with her at this age (she is 7 months old now). I feel oddly blessed and grateful for this time - it has been the best silver lining of this whole experience.
OE_other: I was getting ready to come out of maternity leave and start a private practice when the pandemic started, so my hospital work was as a moonlighter. As such, I had the option of simply not working when the pandemic started and little was known and PPE/testing was less available. I chose not to work until policies changed at my hospital and things began to feel more safe. We took a significant financial hit as a result (I had no income and no benefits), but we are fortunately a two-income household and we made it work. I am back at work now that things feel safer, but not at full time due to lack of child care.

OE_upsetting: Uncertainty in future clinical and research work; anxious and worried
OE_positive: Support from local restaurants and business for healthcare workers

OE_upsetting: My father was concerned he had COVID, made me very worried. Luckily he did not and recovered from whatever illness it was that he had.

OE_upsetting: the most upsetting thing to me is people not taking this seriously and not wearing mask and taking social distancing precautions
OE_positive: makes me really appreciate family and life

OE_upsetting: Hospital decision makers are making financial decisions that adversely affect all but they arent the ones ever stepping into a COVID postive room, ie high paid and not the ones putting their lives at risk
OE_positive: appreciation from covid patients and there families, being with them when others cant be
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: That my ex husband won't let me see our dog. I'm very sad about it.
OE_positive: nothing
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: To many mixed messages between the hospital and university.  Very difficult to deliver messages, when the rules of both organization vary frequently.  This creates issues amongst team members.  This often makes me feel as a failure.
OE_positive: Being involved in COVID Research.  Learning new creative ways of doing things - hopefully - many of the new ways of conducting business will continue.  I have also learned to be more flexible with staff schedules - I now have a better sense of who can work from home and be productive.  I have learned a lot about my team!
OE_other: I hope this goes away soon and as "lock down" is discontinued, that people practice social distancing and wash their hands.  I am afraid of a resurgence and don't want to have to relive the past 8 weeks all over again.

OE_upsetting: hearing about ethics committees. Over hearing conversations about code status
OE_positive: watching my friends and co workers thrive

OE_upsetting: a general feeling of helplessness, as well as feelings of not having any control, worry about money loss, job loss for my kids, any of us actually getting COVID
OE_positive: friends and colleagues reaching out, everyone trying to be a help to one another
OE_other: The SF VA Med Ctr has been really really responsive to patient and employee needs.

OE_upsetting: Ex spouse with mental illness, drug and alcohol problems, hospitalized involuntarily for practically the entire month of March, losing her house, nursing license and her children.
OE_positive: Connecting with someone whom I'd known and worked with for more than a decade and starting a relationship; someone caring, compassionate, patient, thoughtful and the polar opposite of my ex.
OE_other:
I was burned out well prior to the COVID pandemic. I had already met with my leadership team, dropped my hours and was in the process of arranging a sabbatical when COVID happened. Because of a drop in ED volume, my hours dropped even more, I was allowed more time at home with my kids and away from the hospital. I had struggled for three years following my second divorce. My second wife was a nurse who, as I've mentioned, devolved into a life of drugs and alcohol on top of crippling untreated mental illness, hitting rock-bottom coincident with the COVID pandemic. I tried helping her as best I could during the three years since our marriage ended, but in the end, she pushed me and the rest of her family away. At this point, she's lost her house, her nursing license and her kids. In the meantime, in addition to my kids, I take care of my equally mentally feeble mother, with a slew of medical comorbidities including lung cancer. She's been living with  us for two of these past two years. Our relationship isn't good, but I'm her only relative in this country, and feel obligated to help. 
I'm constantly surrounded by work and work-related things. I have administrative duties at the hospital dealing with emergency preparedness, and I am also the EMS coordinator for the local fire department. Therefore, while I'm working less clinical hours these days, I still have lots of other work that brings me to the hospital and to my office at the fire department. I was in need of help, in need of a break before this all started. September was to be my month to take off and collect myself, regroup, and decide how I wanted to proceed in my life and my career. But now it seems that that opportunity has all but evaporated. Meanwhile, I've swallowed down all that hurts me, yet again, and continue to power through my days without missing a beat. I don't see an end in sight, and feel that the best I can do is to enjoy my limited clinical schedule the way it is now and do the best I can to

OE_upsetting: There was a time when I felt physically ill, unsure if it was from COVID or another viral illness. That, in addition to other logistical issues caused by COVID - daycare closing, job duties shifting, continuing to do MPH coursework, was very stressful. It felt like my entire world was crashing down upon me all of a sudden. There were a few days when I felt very hopeless and there was no solution to any of my problems.
OE_positive: Going to the grocery store in scrubs and having stranger walk up to me to thank me for being in healthcare. Helped to remind me what my role was during this pandemic and why I chose to be in medicine.
OE_other: Overall, I have been very disappointed by how the hospital and state has handled issues like childcare that makes it difficult for working parents to continue their jobs. In addition, there is a major concern of bringing home an infectious disease to family members, especially small children. Eventually Yale did find some solutions to both of these issues, but the response was delayed and not robust enough (not enough childcare spots or providers).

OE_upsetting: Not at UCSF, but hearing on the news about hospital staff members on the frontline getting furloughed, paycut, and or reduced work hours due to budget while hospital administration themselves are not affected (and or receiving a raise). It just shows how little they care about the workers.
OE_positive: My interaction with people outside of work ---more encouragement, appreciation, respect.

OE_upsetting: At the start of the pandemic, the most upsetting experience for me was realizing the increased vulnerability of our inpatient psychiatric units and patients to COVID (inability to provide true respiratory isolation for more than a couple patients on the unit if necessary, with patients who are often elderly and have medical comorbidities), and feeling that we didn't have system-wise preparedness in case of a surge.  As a resident in the inpatient setting, it was frustrating to wait for plans to be created and then disseminated, and to see how a traditionally reactive system that is a massive bureaucracy takes time to respond when rapid change is necessary.  It was additionally quite angering to see disparities between how institutions of different sizes and financial security were more or less able to provide rapid or even in-house COVID testing.
OE_positive: Seeing how our strong inpatient team dynamics and interprofessional relationships, as well as compassionate inter-residency dynamics, have allowed for increased peer support and teamwork during a particularly stressful time, has been both gratifying and inspiring.  Both on the inpatient units and in residency didactic sessions, we are still able to share moments of joy and humor, and to recognize the deep humanity of our work (even when wearing masks), and that helps prevent burnout.
OE_other: It's a deep privilege to be a physician during this time, and I am grateful for near-daily reminders that I chose the right career.  More than ever, this job feels like a calling.

OE_upsetting: Unable to visit my family.  Sad, lonely, depressed, worried.
OE_positive: Appreciation of the beautiful planet earth and nature right out my doorstep.

OE_upsetting: Loss of connection with my team members and feeling more isolated
OE_positive: taking time over lunch to take walks and experience nature. Being with my dog more.

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting thing is the non uniform way that we offer life supportive care. It seems like we are picking and choosing who we push towards CMO and who we even offer a ventilator to. A 90 yo patient was sent in with respiratory failure secondary to cover and she wasn't offered ventilation despite further decompensation and was sent home to die, yet we are keeping others with no change alive for weeks on the vent, ECMO, and CVVH. To me this doesn't seem fair, makes me feel shady with the way information is presented to people
OE_positive: Positive is that I haven't had to see patients and have been able to work remotely
OE_other: This is too much and I want debt relief

OE_upsetting: Attendance at a CSection (I was there to attend to the baby), wearing full PPE and my face shield fogged up so badly that I couldn't see.  I was in sterile gown and gloves, so I couldn't fix it myself.  I did get help from the circulating nurse, but the shield fogged again before the baby was born.  How was I going to care for my patient if I couldn't see her?  I was very upset about the situation.  (In the end, the fogging ebbed a little, and fortunately, the baby was healthy).
OE_positive: In general, patient families are much more expressive of their gratitude for the care they are receiving and for the hospital staff caring for them.  Also, the families of my babies seem to be more understanding of the visiting restrictions in place - I had expected much more push-back and complaining.
OE_other: I work at four different hospitals in both Connecticut and California.  Although I understanding some of the reasons for the differences, I find the huge variation in hospital protocols surrounding what PPE is worn in certain situations, PPE reuse policies and specific approaches to care of babies with respiratory issues (specifically whether or not full PPE is required) very challenging.

OE_upsetting: worrying that I harmed a patient with my care. Felt guilty, but relieved when I later found out it wasn't my actions that caused a problem and the patient was doing well
OE_positive: saving money, reconnecting with old friends, time to do things I didn't have time to do before

OE_upsetting: my parents were supposed to come stay with us for 2 months starting mid-April and had to cancel trip because of COVID-19. Big source of support, both emotionally and practically. Very sad not to have them nearby, worried about them in this, but also would have felt incredibly guilty if we had exposed them. So recognize they are safer isolating, but also frightened I may never see them alive again
OE_positive: spending more quality weekend time with my children, which has been wonderful. going on walks with them, snuggling, listening to audiobooks together during drive into the city for work (have to drop them off at childcare, since school closed).

OE_upsetting: The announcement that despite me being a front line health care worker who is literally in the face of COVID+ patients, my income is likely to be 20% lower than it was last year.

The most upsetting thing is that many people believe this is a hoax, and think they should be able to continue to live normally. It makes me feel like our society is doomed, that selfish ignorant people don’t care how many people die or how many they possibly cause to die.  I am so afraid that we will have an onslaught of ill people and not have sufficient manpower or supplies to help them as seen in NYC and Milan
OE_positive: I received cards from neighbors offering to help me should I need to stay extra at work or should I get sick
OE_other: I am disgusted that I have to wear ONE surgical mask all week, that I have to wear ONE N95 mask until it APPEARS worn out, that there are SO MANY false negative covid tests.  I am SO GRATEFUL to everyone that does stay home and socially distances themselves so we have not had the surge in RI and CT that was originally predicted

OE_upsetting: My mother being in a nursing home and unable to see her. After a month was able to get her home with 24 hr care but fearful of exposing her so very limited contact.

OE_other: It has been great seeing and feeling all  the support from the community.

OE_upsetting: My immunocompromised father lives with me. He has a wound vac on due to hip replacement surgery. It's getting deeper, not less deep. He's picked up a secondary rare infection. I wonder if I've brought it home from work. I have not seen my son in 2 months. He's 7. We have less and less staff and less and less PPE and more and more stress.
OE_positive: There is nothing.
OE_other:
I love my job, but not right now. I did not sign up to work in a pandemic without sufficient amounts of PPE. The CDC doesn't care about us - standards change frequently to reflect what supplies there are, not what actually would protect healthcare workers the most. At best, all healthcare workers will have to work to break the bad habits that we are being forced to form now. Previously, JCAHO would have dinged us if they saw us reuse a mask or gown. Now, we have no choice in the matter at all. We have had to break years and years of training. Perhaps some of us will never regain that same discipline. Who knows? 
We will not forget what is happening in hospitals throughout our nation. We will not forget. And we will not forgive.
That being said, my particular facility's manager of our department is excellent, and I know she genuinely cares about each and every one of us. She is being put in a terrible position herself, and doing the best job that she knows how to do.

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting thing has been reading in the media that there are folks out there who think this is a hoax and that we are making it up in order to receive monitary benefits from the government. We are putting our lives at risk every day we come to work and people are thinking there is a secondary gain. It makes me feel so unappreciated. It also makes me fear that people like that will be more likely to take risks and have higher potential to pass this virus onto others.
OE_positive: I enjoy the fact that I see more people getting outdoors and walking around, jogging, bicycling, etc. It makes me happy to see people taking a break from their electronics and enjoying mother nature!
OE_other: It makes me a little sad seeing how people avoid each other now. Some people are aggressive in avoiding others and I wonder how this will carry out in the future.

OE_upsetting: There are too many things to choose from.  Obviously the loss of patients and the disconnect from their families is horrible, but I truly feel like the bedside nurses are doing an excellent job of taking care of the patients and their loved ones, as they always do during end-of-life in our ICU.  For me personally, probably feeling torn between my strong relationship with the bedside nurses, and now being in a management role.  Working long extra hours, and giving 200% to make sure everyone is safe, informed and appreciated, but seeing constant negative social media posts from staff members, online petitions about poor working conditions and anti-establishment/administration media.  I realize that people are likely referring to upper level corporate leadership, but it is hard not to take it personally when staff discuss concerns about "management".  My priority is taking care of the patients, but now my role is also to oversee the staff (who are also still my close friends), and I am doing everything possible to make sure everyone has what they need, so to hear that they do not feel supported or safe makes me feel like I am failing at my job.
OE_positive:
(I drink alcohol less often because I worry about needing to come in at any time to assist with staffing the unit)

It is hard to feel hopeful when the timeline for COVID at this point feels never ending.  The community support has been positive, although it doesn't really feel like it is for me, it is meant for the bedside staff.
OE_other: I feel like there was initially a surge of people jumping in to the cause, signing up for OT, coming to work from other units.  I worry that as this becomes what now seems like an inevitably longer crisis, those staff are going to become burnt out, and our issues with things like staffing and supplies will actually get worse, not better.  I fear that we are just beginning, and I don't know if staff or myself have the resiliency to continue working at this level for an extended period of time.

OE_upsetting: I have been working in the MICU for about a month.  So I have known my patients quite well and they have been very sick.  Once day I noticed one of my patients on a ventilator looked horrible the way he was breathing (he was gasping).  The doctors just started to round on him.  He was still on very high vent settings and I asked if they were coming down on his sedation and the nurse basically bit my head off stating that "we can't keep these patients sedated forever and that he was coughing" She was wrong he was not coughing he was gasping.  The doctors agreed he needed more sedation.  Then the entire day she was to be blunt a "bitch" to me.  These patients are extremely ill and I know my job being in Respiratory and she had no business trying to do mine.  She was rude the entire day to me because I spoke up for the patient.  We should not have to put up with this type of behavior ever.  I spoke to my manager and supervisor, but to be honest she is the type of person if you say something to her it will not matter she will not change the way she acts.
OE_positive: I just feel blessed on how the community has come together and helped out with everything from food, masks, caps.
OE_other: I think overall, my co-workers have tried to help out and everyone seems to be very understanding.  I just was hard at times when the policies on how we were doing things kept on changing.  First we couldn't do things a certain way then it was ok.  It would just make us wonder if it really was ok and safe to do.

OE_upsetting:
When the pandemic first started, the COVID Command Center at my hospital did a very poor job at implementing infection control procedures.  Only 1-2 patients per day were being put on precautions and anyone else coming in with respiratory symptoms was treated under normal procedure.  A patient came in for asthma exacerbation x 5 days after her medrol dose pak was not treating her symptoms.  My coworker and I (both pregnant) sent for her to come to the XRay department.  She came wearing a mask improperly.  We xrayed her with only gloves on and sent her back to the ED.  90 minutes later another coworker happened to notice that the patient had a COVID precautions symbol next to her name in the ED Trackboard that had not been in place prior to us performing her exam.  Less than 2 days later that patient was intubated up on the CCU.  

The reason that it was so upsetting was that the experts and professionals that were in charge of implementing the COVID infection control procedures did a terrible job of providing staff with proper procedures and policies.  In addition to that, there were several staff members that were exposed to COVID from this one patient prior to her being deemed a COVID risk.  After that, there was no handoff in communication to notify any of that staff that they had been potentially exposed. Not only had our health been put at risk but I had to take time out of caring for patients to call and email my supervisor, the Command Center, Employee Health, the transportation department, and the transportation department manager.
OE_positive: I went for a walk on my lunch break one day and someone pulled their car over to thank me for working during this outbreak.  It made me happy to know that she would take time out of her day to thank me.
OE_other: I hope that all healthcare workers feel appreciated. I hope that the pandemic can be brought under control and we are able to avoid, control, or treat it successfully should we face this challenge again.

OE_upsetting: The stress it placed on my wife worrying about me performing my duties as an ED Doctor.  I don't worry about much but this whole pandemic has really increased her anxiety and depression to the point she had to seek help
OE_positive: I feel even more drawn to my career in Emergency Medicine and more understand the important role in plays in my life

OE_upsetting: watching patient die that normally are in good health.
OE_positive: working with such positive staff Respiratory and nursing
OE_other: appreciate all the support from the hospital all the venders that send in food and snacks.

OE_upsetting: No access to N95 masks
OE_positive: Weather got better- that’s nice

OE_upsetting: Feeling responsible for so many colleagues and so many patients has skyrocketed my anxiety
OE_positive: Getting married helped!!! Also, Getting a psychologist to help me process everything
OE_other: The financial strain on our health systems is unbelievable! In this middle of a health care crisis, we are all going bankrupt, laying off workers, taking pay cuts. Society says they appreciate us, but I'm bitter that what is see is my colleagues laid off, and my pay cut, despite a dramatic increase in hours worked. Society says they appreciate health care workers, but yet, we are NOT supported. Our federal government needed to step in to insure everyone in the country had access to the same protocols, treatments, and care without health care workers having to be laid off, pay cut, and working many more hours and taking many more risks. Treating us like this is deplorable. If people truly cared about us, they would recognize that this isn't about politics, its about taking care of each other, and health care workers are not being taken care of by society. The opposite has happened. Makes me feel so ill, how we've all been treated.

OE_upsetting: Seeing my first intubation in the ED with a patient my age who was much healthier than I am. Seeing someone struggling to breathe like that has been in the back of my mind since then.
OE_positive: Nothing because I still have no answers to this situation. Even when we hear of all the patients being discharged its always followed up with talk of the next surge or the next spike because of the restrictions being lifted.
OE_other: The lack of planning was shocking. The amount of time behind this hospital was from the rest of the health system was staggering and the fact that information wasn't given to the team's across the board was crazy. Everyone in this hospital has separated themselves into teams and are not working towards the same goal. It's very disappointing and shocking that people can't get on the same page.

OE_upsetting: unable to get paprs/hoods at my hospital

Afterward I was angry & sad. I reconciled with her & felt much better, but it required me to acknowledge & announce the feelings I had.

OE_upsetting: We have not had enough PPE and have to reuse it. We don't even have enough bouffant caps and have to wear them over and over. The straps on our N95s are loose, and the masks don't always fit properly. There are not set in stone protocols for anything. Rules and regulations are changing everyday leaving people questioning the right and safe things to do.

OE_upsetting:
Being sick and told to stay out of work BUT not being tested until day 14 of symptoms.  Then having to tell my team I was positive, but at suck a late date that it angered and creates some panic in my department. 
The lack of available tests and protocol for who and when to test caused a lot of stress

OE_upsetting: Working in the overflow make-shift ICUs made me fearful of the pandemic for the first time. It reminded me of a M*A*S*H unit or a war zone.  Also, disallowing family to be present with patients feels Draconian.  If we say we have figured out how to keep healthcare workers “safe” enough to care for COVID patients and HCWs families, then why can’t we figure out how to keep family members safe?
OE_positive: Quick access to research articles.  College kids at hone with the younger kids.  More time at home.
OE_other: Getting a pay cut in the face if being asked to perform higher risk care in more stressful situations feels wrong.  Feeling like we don’t have enough PPE is because the avge HCW doesn’t have ACCESS to it.  Patients should not be deprived of their families when their ill.

OE_upsetting: Being re-appropriated to a medical intensive care role.  I feel unprepared and inadequate.
OE_positive: The most positive experience was been away from the hospital a lot more due to a decrease in elective surgeries and having the ability to exercise, complete tasks and errands, and bond with my girlfriend.  I felt much better.
OE_other: I just wish that I was not longer a resident physician at this time.

OE_upsetting: A patient lied about his positive test and i was in the room X-ray-ing him when his wife told the ER staff he was positive. I only had a surgical mask on and he had no mask on. Made me feel frustrated that someone would lie especially when in a healthcare facility and also angry that the ER staff did not have him put a mask on.
OE_positive: Everyone in the hospital and out of the hospital coming together regardless of how stressed we all are.

OE_upsetting: I intubated a patient, who was inappropriately rushed to the OR by the surgical team, without any PPE, just a surgical mask. She tested covid positive. I was kept on duty. There is no policy at Loyola for residents to have an n95 on for all intubations. We don’t feel safe or protected at our hospital. Additionally per guidelines I didnt even qualify for testing unless I spiked a fever. How does this align with strong evidence of asymptomatic viral shedding? I feel like I was forced into martyrdom and not protected by my institution nor the national guidelines of proper protection and testing.
OE_positive: Support of nurses and other residents.
OE_other: The abuse and lack of care for safety and protection for nurses and residents is shameful.

OE_upsetting: Being furloughed and having the only available work be in a COVID icu with no ability to separate myself from my family to keep them safe.

OE_upsetting: My family (those that don't live with me) almost seem "afraid" of me. There is a "stigma" about me carrying covid because I work around it. There is always a fear that I could be carrying the disease however they have a hard time understanding that I am protected when I wear my PPE correctly and that I am not "exposed" during those times. It hurts me that they don't understand.
OE_positive: Being a nurse for Covid patients during the outbreak has solidified why I became a nurse. Nurses care. Nurses have empathy and nurses are advocates for their patients. This has never been so apparent. When I see my Covid patients, I am the only person they will see on my entire shift face to face. I then give report to the next nurse and that nurse will be the only healthcare provider that the patient sees face to face. Patients cannot have family members visit. Doctors rarely go in the covid rooms and oftentimes video conference with the patient if they need to speak to or see them. Oftentimes these doctors are doing this from home and are not present in the hospital. Housekeepers do not go in the rooms, nursing empties trash and linen carts now. Dietary does not go in the rooms, nurses now deliver patient's meals. Transport staff do not go in patient rooms, it is the nurse's responsibility to get the patient safely to the stretcher. These patient's are scared and alone and the only person they see is me. This is a nurse's calling. This is what we were trained to do. We are there for the patients when no one else can be.

OE_upsetting: Seeing people loose jobs, and family members.

OE_upsetting: rather not say

OE_upsetting: As a single resident living somewhere not close to family or many friends, the social quarantine does take a toll on social well-being, interactions, human connection. So for me it is just something else that comes with the job that I do no think people outside of the medical field consider. In additional to the years and sacrifice that many individuals in medical education and training programs give up to get to where they are.

OE_upsetting: nothing has happened to me personally

OE_upsetting: I had to transfer two patients from my ward to the COVID ward - both had significant underlying illness.  I had taken care of both for 2 weeks.  One was strongly attached to our service and team, young, newly wed, and died a month later in the ICU.  I struggle with feelings of guilt that I abandoned the patient.  I can't bring myself to make a condolence call to his wife.  He told me he knew he was going to die on the day of his transfer; I reassured him to stay strong and think positively.  I can't help but feel like I not only abandoned him, but that I lied to him.  It was a very difficult time, very early on in the first weeks of the pandemic. It also reaffirms some of my career long struggles with the emotional bonds we form with patients and their families - why we connect with some and not with others, why some deaths affect us so profoundly and others don't...  I realize this is perhaps professional and not personal, but it affected me personally.  I suppose the most upsetting thing that has happened personally is just the disparate opinions of the pandemic in my household and a feeling of psychological isolation (but that is nothing new - I've had a 30 year relationship with a spouse who's worldview is radically different from mine). I feel helpless, isolated.  I don't feel hopeless, though.
OE_positive:
I really enjoyed bringing families to morning bedside rounds via phone or FaceTime.  It made me and the team feel very connected to the patients and their families.  It allowed me to evaluate how the House Staff informs patients with their family members present of their plan and the pathophysiology of their disease in lay terms.  It helped families stay connected while they couldn't visit personally.  I'd like to keep this practice part of daily rounds going forward.

I have a colleague who checks in with me every day.  It's nice to see his text every day.  I'm touched that he cares as much as he does.
OE_other: Thinks have gotten far better now than they were in the beginning in terms of information and PPE in the workplace.  In the beginning, things were disorganized.  Both YNHH and VACT are doing an excellent job keeping their staff updated.

OE_upsetting: Having my son's college education and application to medical school process compromised.
OE_positive: I am feeling relieved that I have time to catch up on backlogs of work at the office and home while the world is put on hold.
OE_other: I am limiting the surgeries I do and find the hospital is dealing with this appropriately. I find those who refuse to social distance and wear masks, as well as criminals very irritating. I think there should be bigger negative consequences for socially unacceptable behaviors and crimes performed during this time.

OE_upsetting: When my 93 year old grandmother was rushes to the hospital with a bad cough and prevented her from breathing. She tested positive for Covid 19. Thankfully she recovered and is better. After that it became a chain reaction as more and more family members tested positive. It was awful to get bad news but couldn't do anything to help. That's when my anxiety and stress level got worse.
OE_positive: It was nice how people came together to help first response, healthcare workers etc.

OE_upsetting: Not being around family and friends as much. Sad.
OE_positive: Saving money

OE_upsetting: I was floated to a COVID-19 floor with a mix of confirmed COVID-19 patients and rule outs was denied a N95 from my management because I am a CNA and they said only nurses needed them because there was a shortage. Letting me know that my ranks weren't high enough in the healthcare field for them to care. That floor did not have enough PPE so when I left a confirmed patients room I had to walk around with all my infected PPE looking for cavi wipes or looking for any PPE that was necessary because they weren't being mindful of stocking the equipment. This whole pandemic only doctors and nurses have been treated like gold while the rest of the roles in a hospital get looked past like we don't matter.
OE_positive: The only good thing that has come from this pandemic is being able to enjoy my family because everything is shut down.
OE_other: I was confifent that working in a hospital through all this would be the ideal place i.e workers and patients but in all reality is the worst place. Have seriously been considering leaving the healthcare field in total.

OE_upsetting: Spouse (also a healthcare worker) has significant anxiety re: COVID-19 and was exposed in the hospital. This has put additional tension/emotional investment on our relationship and put more strain on our family costs raising small children and working.
OE_positive: Spending more time with my children and spouse. I made me feel happy.

OE_upsetting: Co-Workers were very agitated and anxious about the lack of instruction of PPE use  in the operating room at the beginning. Anesthesia was focused on wearing N95s, but no one else in the room was. We were getting conflicting answers from the managers/administration about how to be safe in the operating room for all patients. It was very frustrating to be told to  conserve PPE, and watch other team members waste it because they didn't care. And continue to talk about their anxieties and spread them to others - rather than support each other, it just added fuel to the fire. Once a formal decision and policy was put in place, it was much easier.
OE_positive: I got redeployed to the testing center - great team to work with, already had been established guidelines. Very positive environment and supportive. Also rewarding to interact and help so many nervous patients each day.
OE_other: In talking to other departments, it is a challenge to understand which patients fall under what category, and when you travel to another department - their procedures may not match yours, causing unneccessary stress between staff. (i.e. patient went STAT  to OR with COVID test pending for nursing home - floor treated patient without special precautions. OR treated patient as PUI and therefore berated transport staff with patient for not wearing PPE - made them wait as patient was bleeding out to come to OR. - Lack of clear communication and guidance.)

OE_upsetting: Having no support from management when doing COVID positive cases in the operating room. We have to operate in the MAIN OR instead of our own, their staff does not support us, our management is not present and we get stuck past our scheduled hours with no thank you or form of appreciation. Not sure if we're even properly following policy on how to don and doff because no resources available and being told by other staff "well you don't do these as often as us" so we're doing it "wrong". Anesthesia is allowed to follow their own set of rules while surgical staff has separate rules.
OE_positive: I have a job
OE_other: Pure chaos. Lack of communication between departments.

OE_upsetting: My father has become ill, with things other than COVID-19. I can not go visit him and he has been in and out of the hospital, so I am concerned for his safety.
OE_positive: Grateful that I have had a job throughout this pandemic and a strong support system, both at work and at home.  My hospital has been outstanding and I feel that the administration puts the employees first.

OE_upsetting: A patient of mine going through a manic episode who concurrently tested positive for Covid-19 escaped his room. the staff was exhausted and upset we had to deal with this situation.
OE_positive: The staff has been acting as a supportive family. We help each other out with everything now.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: The most upsetting thing is the financial hardship that comes from loss of clinical income. Dipping into savings to survive creates financial stress that I did not expect.
OE_positive: The chance to catch up on writing research publications.
OE_other: none

OE_upsetting: My office staff was most worried about getting infected and bringing it home to their families. I felt like they blamed the doctors for still seeing patients and patients who were infected with COVID.
OE_positive: The public response to health to health care workers has been heart warming most of the time.  The team work attitude to helping everyone--patients, staff (ALL STAFF from RN's, MD's, residents, housekeepers, food service workers) to stay safe and help the patients has been very nice to see. More of the people at work seem to be more selfless.
OE_other: It hasn't been as bad as I feared it would at the beginning.  I think CT has been lucky to be not as bad as NYC but close enough to learn lessons.

OE_upsetting: We do not have much to offer to COVID-19 patients at this moment apart from supportive treatment. This thing makes me upset sometimes.
How quickly and quietly citizens have given up their liberties.  It makes me disappointed and sad.
OE_positive: The teamwork at the institution in response to the situation.  It made me feel proud of the team and the institution.
OE_other: I fear the economic costs to the institution, and to society are going to be extraordinary.

OE_upsetting: losing my position temporarily from the anesthesia department since surgeries are down and having to go into the Reserves where I tested people for Covid, screening at entrances of hospital and gave out masks to employees. From week to week did not know if I would have hours anywhere or where I would be working. And I never got full time hours. Furlowed for 3 days at home
OE_positive: The support from community for healthcare worker, appreciation
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: I missed seeing and celebrating my daughters birthday. We are both healthcare professionals working in different hospitals in different cities. Travel was restricted for both and we can't take a chance and infect each other. It makes me miss her!
OE_positive: I have spent more time with my pets! Despite working more hours, when I am off I am home with them!
OE_other: This disease is so unpredictable and not much is known about it. I am proud of the work we are doing despite the rapid pace at which things change.

OE_upsetting: Being a full time employee and single mother of 3 children that are old enough to stay home alone, but also trying to keep them motivated to do their home schooling, all while really busy with work during the day. I feel very stressed and overwhelmed.
OE_positive: Kind words and emotional support from cowrkers. I felt stronger having an outlet to express feelings
OE_other: N/A

OE_upsetting: Seeing parents at my child's daycare without a mask and not practicing social distancing
Me and my department being the ones expected to handle all intubations on covid patients throughout the hospital.
OE_positive: Thanks from non medical people and their gratitude towards me for the job I do.
OE_other: Communication from leadership/administration is completely disconnected from what is actually taking place in the clinical areas.

OE_upsetting: Having patient assignments I’m not used to dealing with and not knowing what to do.  This happens every shift, every shift is anxiety provoking.
OE_positive: I have tried to do hole exercising.  I have also had very good conversations with family and friends.
OE_other: It’s been one of the most stressful times of my young life.

OE_upsetting: Covering a Medicine/COVID floor when I am not trained to and being expected to have difficult conversations with families.
OE_positive: It's been positive talking to family members of COVID+ patients in the hospital that share their appreciation for the work we are doing.

OE_upsetting: During the initial COVID surge I was working at the pediatric hospital. While other hospitals as well as the adult side of my hospital were making major adjustments and being overrun with duties, my workload was significantly less than it would normally be. I felt for a long time like an impostor and not being helpful during this time of need. However, that did change once I transitioned to different rotations. I felt more involved and helpful during these times.
OE_positive: The connectedness with family and friends out of state through virtual means.

OE_upsetting: Putting more work on less people to do it because of deployment or work from home by team members. No consideration of this. No consideration that the patients also use this office for help when panicked or for resources due to Covid in addition to rheumatology  concerns. Criticized for voicing staff stress.
OE_positive: Co-workers (nurses) supporting each other and understand the stress bolster one another daily and work hard to do that. Keep going because of them and the patients.
OE_other: I forces one to plan for a better future and appreciate what you have. Forces you to find more ways to help others and be good to yourself for your hard work.

OE_upsetting: I was going to start trying to have children this year and I cant find an OB who will pull my IUD.  Frankly, it made me feel like Ive given up the last 15 years of my life to help take care of other people, but when I want something, no one will do the same for me.
OE_positive: My husband and I have a really good relationship and we’ve been happy quarantined together.

OE_upsetting: People accusing health care workers of labeling people covid to make more money
OE_positive: Support from the community for nurses
OE_other: Exhaustion is an understatement

OE_upsetting: My wife doing nothing for our 20th anniversary on April 29
OE_positive: nothing really
OE_other: It has been controlled and well executed but very stressful

OE_upsetting: Changing my schedule to intubate Covid Patients
OE_positive: Helping others
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Not being able to see my parents because of my known exposures to COVID-19 patients; walking into a patient's room BEFORE he was even a PUI without adequate PPE; this increased my sense of anxiety
OE_positive: signing up for therapy for the first time in my life; it has been a great addition where I get an hour to talk about whatever I want and how it affects me
OE_other: Resident burn out will be even more evident after this settles and I hope that residencies are doing their part in anticipation of this.

OE_upsetting: N/A
OE_other: N/A

OE_upsetting: Physicians don’t want to get involved in intubations. They rely on anesthesia providers to be exposed even though they have those skills
OE_positive: More aware of other viruses such as flu. I will clean grocery carts every time
OE_other: We need our medications made in the USA!

OE_upsetting: We were mandated to work as healthcare screeners on top of our regular work duties. It was unpaid.
OE_positive: The kids in the pediatric hospital (UICH), which is separate but in the center of our medical campus, made signs thanking everyone, including clinical research. You can see them from the window as you walk in to the hospital. I'm certain it was a childlife activity but I treasured it. Each floor (12 floors) made different signs - one was spelling happy messages out in Post-It notes. It was somehow a sign of solidarity : thank you, we are here, we are thankful you are here, and you make an impact. Clinical research has had a rough go of it and we are constantly pivoting. We have to fight to keep pediatric and adult trials open on our campus - and all the contingency plans. I have had to create and adapt all those plans and get them FDA approved. It made it worth it.
OE_other: Our hospital - like many others - had some work from home to reduce foot traffic. This was for about 6 weeks. I was one of those that was asked to work from home (as I could). Remarkably, this created a rift amongst staff and faculty, who felt jaded if they "had" to work and others "got to" work from home. I didn't expect that.

OE_upsetting: I was pulled back to in patient from out patient after 3 years out of  ICU and at first I was fearful but once I got my N100 Mask I felt completely safe at work. Have actually had a good experience doing critical care again.
OE_positive: I have regained my clinical skills for in patient and been able to see many of my co workers I enjoy working with but don't see in out patient
OE_other: I feel like Yale did a good job

OE_upsetting: seeing my children's reactions to the loss of things
OE_positive: Seeing people recover

OE_upsetting: I miss shopping with my husband, now only one of us goes to get groceries.
OE_positive: Spent a day with my brother and his family.  It was so nice to do "normal" and not worry about social distancing.
OE_other: No thank you.

OE_upsetting: I am a compassionate conservative and my views are belittled by the ruling elite at my institution
OE_positive: feeling that most health care providers have put needs of patients ahead of their own.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Have not been in the same state as my wife since the Superbowl.
Not being able to get together with friends and family for birthday's, graduation, weddings and holidays.  Makes me feel disappointed.
OE_positive: Allowed more time with family.  It has been stressful, but has allowed us to come together and be creative with activities.
OE_other: Thankful for the PPE that is given to us to keep us as safe as possible.

OE_upsetting: don't know
OE_positive: don't know
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Had initially been considered high risk and sent home to quarantine. my supervisor called me that same day and reports with further discussion my risk was low and I was to return to work the next day.
OE_positive: Feeling appreciated by the community

OE_upsetting: Unable to see my family because of my exposure.  I'm afraid to give it to my older parents.
OE_positive: Nothing
OE_other: A lot of work with little rewards

OE_upsetting: I have decided not to get within 6 feet of my parents (whom are over 60) or visit with my adult siblings and their families during this time.  I shared this early on in the pandemic and they were upset with me and my mother even hung up on me on the phone.  I feel isolated from my family.
OE_positive: It seems like society as a whole appreciates hospital workers and there have been perks at different businesses.

OE_upsetting: I have had to start taking overnight call again assignment to intubate all COVID patients and line them up (3 times in last month). Sleep and worry very poor these nights. NOT to be political but the lies that come out of the White House make my job more difficult and I am concerned about a resurgence when we already have had to creat 2 ICU units housing 30 COVID patients. The public just doesn't seem to get it. Last night driving home there was a picketer outside the hospital dressed in a Scream outfit with a sign "Resist Medical Tyranny" ugh
OE_positive: The coming together of community including colleagues to work on extremely difficult issues. Support from all our families
