OE_positive: PRAYING / MAKES ME FEEL GOOD
OE_other: TEAMWORK

OE_upsetting: Watching a newborn baby die after coding her for 15 minutes.  The mom was covid+ and her hypercoagulability caused clotting of the placental vessels essentially killing the kid.  Because mom wasn’t healthy, COVID is decimating her as well.  That’s just one of many examples.
OE_positive: Watching people come off the ventilator and make it out of the hospital...makes you feel like your really helping some of them.

OE_upsetting: I have lost several family members and had several confirmed positive members including my mother.
OE_positive: i have no idea
OE_other: Nope

OE_upsetting: Having to practice outside my subspecialty (Orthopaedics) and manage Hospitalist (Medical) COVID, non COVID, and patients under investigation.  I wouldn't say this upsetting per se but stressful.  Especially because their staffing "shortage" was self inflicted when the Hospitalist service went to 12 hour shifts.  This led to a loss of Advanced Practitioner providers.  I don't mind helping out during these difficult times, I just don't want to hurt someone because I make a mistake.
OE_positive: Spending more time with my wife and daughter.  It has reinforced how much I love them.
OE_other: It has been a bit stressful with no foreseeable end in sight.  This is fatiguing, scary, and somewhat depressing but I can't imagine doing anything else.  I fell honored to be a healthcare provider.

OE_upsetting: Working just as hard or harder to take care of patients and assuage their fears - I feel unappreciated by the senior members in my group.
OE_positive: I appreciate the outpouring of support from the community and the recognition of how hard doctors work.

OE_upsetting: N/A
OE_positive: n/a

OE_upsetting: I was exposed to a COVID positive patient in the OR because of a breach of protocol in the ED and was not notified for 3 hours of caring for the patient.
OE_positive: We had our first intubated patient recover and go home.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Thinking that one of my family members may be infected. I was scared for them.

Had to cancel several family events. (50th B-day party & Spring Break vacation).  I was upset more for my child.  His/her world has been turned upside down with distance learning and not being able to see his/her friends and family.  Even though he/she understands why the cancellations needed to happen, it still stinls.
OE_positive: My family has been able to slow down our lifestyle.  We were constantly on the go. Now we spend more time outdoors at home. My yard has never looked better. I like to spend time outdoors where it is peaceful. Our pets are so happy to have us around all this time and we are enjoying their constant companionship. I am cooking more meals at home and we are eating healthier. It feels great to lead a less chaotic lifestyle.

OE_upsetting: Stress with friends/family/colleagues who did not respect/follow guidelines strictly, in particular those who are medically trained. I had a disagreement with my father, a doctor, over his not distancing strictly enough. This disagreement caused significant stress to our relationship.
OE_positive: As a resident, typical milestones in diagnosis/surgery. Various small and large moments of feeling like I helped someone. These were not generally COVID-related.
OE_other: Nothing specific.

OE_upsetting: Being distant from my family and fear of getting them sick
OE_positive: One of my patients leaving the hospital after being intubated from COVID.

OE_upsetting: Having to be transferred to cover medicine patients and feeling worried that I would miss or mismanage something.  I felt like I was being put in a position out of my comfort zone. I continue to feel anxious about having to manage medicine patients.
OE_positive: Despite our reassignment, our immediate ortho team has been very supportive of one another.

OE_upsetting: Several of my primary  care patients have died from non- covid related causes. They were patients with significant co-morbidities who were hesitant to  come to the hospital early for evaluation.
OE_positive: Many friend express gratitude for what I  do.

OE_upsetting: My entire unit, which is pre-op and PACU, had either different hours or roles. Since we had stopped doing elective surgeries, many of my colleagues were deployed to the designated COVID ICUs. To see the effect this caused on my fellow nurses was/is devastating . Some felt like they were thrown into the ICU and did not feel comfortable because it had been years since they worked in an ICU. I found myself working nights and picking up extra hours and call because most of our staff was gone. Working nights is very hard for me. I have been flip flopped from days to nights in the same week. I feel tired all the time and find it difficult to sleep. I had to go to many rapid response calls on the floors because the patients that were sicker were moved to the floors so they could make room in the ICUs and step downs. I felt that it was my responsibility to be flexible and reminded myself that at least I wasn’t deployed to where the sickest patients were.
OE_positive: That I got to see my family more.
OE_other: During this time, protocols and the way we do things are changing every day. Sometimes more frequently. I feel in the past week, these changes are positive. I finally feel like- Okay, this is the protocol. I pray for the days where work is normal, but fear that it will never be back to normal. Many of my friends are still working in the ICUs. The thing I feared the most was not knowing where I was working or what hours I was working. It felt good to help out at the COVID testing tent, where I worked for a few days. I thought that at least I had all the protective gear on while I worked there. The fear of not knowing if people had the virus before the patients were being tested preoperatively was overwhelming. We only started testing all the patients in the past week or so.

OE_upsetting: changing hours due to lack of childcare, working later hasn't helped. Also the fact that working in a facility that has the highest amount of Covid-19 cases
OE_positive: the outpouring of gratitude towards healthcare workers and the thanks from businesses
OE_other: Just an eye-opening experience being on the frontline during a pandemic crisis. makes me appreciate what I have

OE_upsetting: My boyfriend is unemployed and unhappy
OE_positive: I stopped drinking alcohol, so I have slept more deeply and am now able to think more clearly

OE_upsetting: There isn't a particular event that has upset me.  It has been overwhelming being called to work on Internal Medicine floors when I normally work in Orthopedics, but I haven't had to do that very often and I've had a lot of support.
OE_positive: The financial support from the hospital has been great.  Although we are working from home every other week we still get paid as if we are at the hospital.  They also gave us a bonus.

OE_upsetting: Having a supervisor on a covid unit be on social media during important discussions instead of contributions to critical patient care
OE_positive: Appreciation from patients and their families for doing our routine care

OE_upsetting: My boyfriend had a family member pass from COVID-19, so he had to go home to be with his family. He works at the hospital and got tested before going home, and was negative. However, while he was there, one of his family members in the house tested positive for COVID, and even though he was exposed, because he was asymptomatic he was not able to get housing so that he could self-isolate (he and I live together). We have not been able to isolate well in our 1 bedroom apartment and I feel very anxious that one or both of us is going to get sick. I feel a lack of control and inability to protect ourselves.
OE_positive: I have been enjoying the spring and due to reduced hours at work have been able to get outside more to exercise frequently with runs and hikes. I have felt happy that I have been able to take care of my physical health in that way.

OE_upsetting: My cat died
OE_positive: Spent a day with friend at beach

OE_upsetting: Watching patients die that most likely would have been alive if they had not contracted this virus, has been upsetting. Watching patient after patient pass away without their family nearby is very difficult. But by far the most disheartening is hearing and seeing the public on social media suggesting that hospitals are making money off covid and that we as providers are exaggerating the mortality rate of this virus, and that we don’t care about the negative consequences of quarantine. It’s the most isolating feeling, and is the reason I have doubted most of the public’s “healthcare hero” initiatives.
OE_positive: Patient called me his “lifesaver” when I discovered his pulmonary embolism. A family member told me I personally helped make her husband’s unfortunate death peaceful for them. Family members of patients thank me and tell me they are praying for my safety. All of these stories make it worth it, and bring me some hope and motivation to keep going. Due to quarantine, my roommate and I have become close friends (prior, we never spent more than an hour together due to our busy work schedules).  Also, earlier on I preemptively reconnected with my old therapist, and it was extremely helpful and has been a positive experience.
OE_other: Internal medicine chief resident Rebecca Slotkin personally provided us residents the most support. Many people worked hard to make this an easier transition, but she went above and beyond and needs to be recognized for this. Could not imagine the added anxiety and stress if we did not have her advocating for us.

OE_upsetting: Working on the COVID ICU and seeing how sick some of the patients were and hearing how many codes there were in the hospital was sad and scary.
OE_positive: More people have been connecting with each other. For example, I received a gift in the mail from a family friend. I was surprised and touched to receive this.
OE_other: n/a

OE_upsetting: Fear for my family and loved ones -- seeing this disease take lives, including those of multiple family members in one household and fearing for the safety/health of and exposure to my immediate family (who I am socially distancing from when I visit).
OE_positive: It's provided a chance to slow down and I'm actually working far fewer hours since the pandemic started (~40 hrs/week instead of the typical 65+) as our resident schedules have changed. The hours that I do work are exhausting -- physically and more so, emotionally as we are taking care of COVID patients 24/7. I cannot imagine how I would be without this modified, reduced hour schedule. This pandemic has helped me prioritize what is important to me (family, loved ones) and what isn't.

OE_upsetting: My sister cut me off emotionally for an unrelated reason. It makes me feel anxious, sad, worried, guilty, shameful.
OE_positive: Comraderie among peers,  better sense of reward in daily work,  more trust and respect from patients families.
OE_other:
I have overall been proud of my hospital, it's leadership, transparency and efforts. 

It's been a weird but interesting time.

OE_upsetting: Being unexpectedly separated from my partner and family who live in a foreign country- normally we see each other regularly. Not knowing how long it will be until we can spend time together is stressful and saddening.
OE_positive: Setting up a regular video chat date with my closest friend. Often we don;t make so much time to see each other as much as we would like. Our video chats are fun, relaxing, and often we reminisce.
OE_other: not at this time

OE_upsetting: Hospital policy restricting family from visiting patients for end of life visits. Per policy family are only allowed to visit once, and must get to hospital within 1 hour. Family got to hospital ~10-15 mins over 1 hour limit and were almost not allowed to see family member who had passed (unexpected passing). Had to fight with nursing to allow family visitation rights.
My mother-in-law had a return of her ovarian cancer.  Angry.
OE_positive: I've worked out a lot more since I have nothing else to do in my free time currently.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: nothing
OE_positive: na

OE_upsetting: That our hospital was initially giving staff a hard time about wearing a mask all the time during working.
OE_positive: Enjoying more family time.
OE_other: Our hospital hand under appreciated the staff during this time.

OE_upsetting: My wedding had to be canceled which was upsetting.
OE_positive: Getting married and getting to spend more time with my husband due to having more days off and him working from home.

OE_upsetting: I was infected with COVID 19 after being floated from my ortho floor to a COVID floor. I was told to rewear and disinfect disposable PPE several times. I never felt safe at my own job. I verbalized numerous times my concern for my safety to the team and middle management. I felt taken advantage of, disposable, like I didn't matter. I stayed in my bedroom for 11 days as my family was terrified of my illness. I did everything I could to prevent being sick. I changed before leaving work, cleaned everything down, brought disposable products (waterbottles, etc.) to work. I still got infected. I go to work and they act as if nothing happened to me. It makes me feel unvalued by my organization. I thank God for my health now. I just feel defeated.
OE_positive: I am much more grateful for my friends. I miss them so much. I can't wait to see them again. I also feel much closer to my co-workers and my family as we get through this together.
OE_other: It's terrible. I wish people knew what it was like to work in a COVID unit. It's a slap in the face to see people "protesting" masks and social distancing. Come see the disease, the fear people have, the dying - all on the front lines. I also feel belittled by hospital administrators that think they know what they are doing. If we were better prepared, maybe it wouldn't have been so chaotic in the first months.

OE_upsetting: Most concerned about infecting my small children at home and other family members.
OE_positive: Nurses helping nurses, i.e. making masks, surgical cap, etc.
OE_other: no.

OE_upsetting: The Fear of the unknown About the virus itself and what the future holds. For example, we don’t know how Or when our work follow with Change. We don’t know when we can socialize with people. We don’t know when it’s safe to send our child to daycare.
OE_positive: More family time. My husband travels for work and has not been traveling for the past 4 weeks. It’s been nice to see him more.
OE_other:
I appreciate All the Regularity of communication Via email and video conference from my boss. I also feel that my group of co-workers are amazing and we are all supportive of each other. 
I wish we didn’t have to re-use PPE and there was more cleanliness of the shared workspaces/computers in designated COVID floors.

OE_upsetting: Having to work outside of my area of expertise and care directly for covid patients on the medicine services. It has made me feel incapable, not knowledgeable, and stressed about getting sick or getting family sick.
OE_positive: Getting to spend more time at home with my children since being allowed to work from home every other week.
OE_other: Orthopedic PA's are being used to take care of covid pts on the medical service with little to no training.

OE_upsetting: Patient with mental status changes and hard of hearing-  not able to get her to understand & feeling I should take off my protective equipment
OE_positive: People getting together to sing made me feel joy at the sounds of joy
OE_other: Being put in position to help other workers (but not in my regular work role) then feeling like I was brought in for no reason- just more exposure that I could have avoided

OE_upsetting: My husband and I are both internal medicine residents, working in direct COVID care. In March, as the pandemic in the US was rapidly worsening, we made the difficulty decision to live separately from our 2 year old son and my mother, who helps us take care of him. We were unable to provide for his childcare on our own since we were both working, and we felt very worried about transmitting the coronavirus to my mother, who is in her late 60s. It has been devastating to live apart from him: As residents and parents, we’ve spent the last two years trying to optimize every free minute with our son. In normal times, I worry constantly about being an adequate parent. Now, I fear that his security in knowing he is loved and the bonds we’ve worked so hard to foster are being broken down by this time apart.
OE_positive: I have felt well-supported by the leadership in our department - the chief residents, program directors, program administrators, departmental leadership - and I have found the communication from the leadership of internal medicine to be transparent (even if sometimes excessive in volume). This made me trust my institution and feel connected to this place, when as a hospital resident here on a limited contract and being moved between many services, that's not always the case.

OE_upsetting: I was surprised that hospitals in the US including my hospital, do not have emergent stocks for PPEs. Each hospital should have had an emergency warehouse to keep enough PPEs to protect staff. Re-using one N95 I was given forever made me feel that I was not protected enough and properly.
OE_positive: I appreciate my hospital and healthcare system provided us 14-days of pandemic sick time offs. I also appreciate them that our healthcare system has not furloughed any employees during this difficult time even though some hospitals among my area did lay off their employees to keep their business.
OE_other: Hospitals, in general, should have a pandemic plan to apply quickly to protect patients and their staff to be efficient. I felt like any hospital was not well-prepared for pandemic events, even though there were several pandemic events in the past.

OE_upsetting: Knowing that my family is afraid to see me physically, even though they are very supportive emotionally/over the phone/zoom, etc.  Our family dog is dying and I haven't been able to spend time with her.
OE_positive: The outpouring of support from friends, family, and the community.

OE_upsetting: A patient on the floor was coding and I could not go in to help because we were trying to limit the number of people going into the room. I later felt very guilty as the nurses who were in the code were worried about their exposure.
OE_positive: Had more opportunity to connect with family and friends over this shared concern

OE_upsetting: I'm torn between lack of PPE that fits me for me to perform my job safely and heart-wrenching patient care situations (patients dying alone, etc).
OE_positive: I have appreciated my program's transparency with the residents regarding any concerns we may have and ongoing decisions

OE_upsetting: My children missing out on their education.  Sad for the future of the education system.  Neighbors fearing neighbors. FEAR. People are afraid of everything.  Politics and this pandemic are tearing our country further apart.
OE_positive: Spending more time with my kids.  Exercising more often.

OE_upsetting: Last minute scheduling changes that negatively effected me and made me feel anxious upset and burnt out at the beginning of the pandemic.
OE_positive: Being able to see my significant other more, to work through things together, and to support one another. To have more time away from work to decompress and spend time on myself and my personal life.
OE_other: No

OE_upsetting: I am new to my position. I did not have privileges when pandemic hit so I have been at home unable to care for patients or help on the front line. Makes me feel worthless as a nurse.
OE_positive: Seeing everyone come together to for the greater good. Seeing the support in the community.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Not being able to spend time with family or friends. Not knowing when I will be able to. Makes me feel isolated and alone
OE_positive: Very good feeling to see how the community has reached out to us and supports us by providing food and snacks to us

OE_upsetting: Unable to participate in cousin’s engagement as planned due to vacation being cancelled. Was upsetting, but able to participate via Zoom
OE_positive: Zoom family meeting to celebrate Mother’s Day. Was a very uplifting and positive experience to catch up with family
OE_other: Covid has been a difficult but interesting time to be a trainee. We have an incredible opportunity to learn in real time and use our clinical skills to develop new treatment options. While the situation is definitely challenging, I think there is a lot to learn and take away from the situation.

OE_upsetting: Watching the politicization of health and the opportunity to release the tyranny that lies within every progressive normally screaming to get out.
OE_positive: Seeing the way our department has responded, how leaders have assumed responsibilities and great shown initiatives to change work flows and manage the mental health of our patients, our front-line staff and more.  The mindset of "team" has been wonderful.

OE_upsetting: Inability to see my family. it makes me sad and I miss them. Sometimes I wonder if and when it will be safe to see them, especially my grandparents.
OE_positive: I feel so much pride in my work and the work that our hospital has done to keep staff safe as much as possible and use evidenced based medicine to care for these patients with good outcomes.
OE_other: It was so incredibly ironic that in the year of the nurse, Nurse's Week 2020 the hospital did very little to celebrate, other than make videos of upper administration thanking us.  It seems very empty. I feel like we deserve more.

OE_upsetting: My family refused to see me. It made me feel unwanted.
OE_positive: The support and teamwork from physicians and nurses I work with.
OE_other: Hardest time of my nursing career.

OE_upsetting: The fact that my hospital doesn’t test all surgery patients. Only certain “high risk” procedures are considered worthy of testing.  These include ENT, OMFS, and GI cases. Most other surgical candidates aren’t tested for COVID.

One of our young patients died because organ transplantation has fallen to really low levels. At any other time he would definitely had gotten an offer and had a chance. It felt unfair to him and the decisions to alter transplant were based on very little data so I am not sure it was justified.
OE_positive: A supermarket worker came up to me and thanked me for my service and gave me a code for 10% for medical workers. I felt appreciated and my sacrifice recognized.
OE_other: Its interesting how different people have risen to the occasion and others have recoiled away from it. We are lucky in our pulmonary group that our leader has embraced and accepted the validity of both responses. That has made us all appreciate the different ways we can each participate. There is no shame here if you are too afraid to care for these patients. That is strangely comforting for those of us who are able to do the work, I don't have to resent those who cannot.

OE_upsetting: Since the pandemic, the most upsetting thing is experiencing mild prejudice given my Asian ethnicity (despite having an American accent and being raised in Mississippi). The blame of the pandemic is clearly on wet market practices in China (with potential more outbreaks in other countries like South America that possess similar practices), but the anxious lay person is irrationally blaming all descendants from that region (not just its native citizens). The majority of people I have come into contact with have not shown any aggression towards me but a minority that projects their negativity towards an ethnic target is enough to make one paranoid.
OE_positive: The most positive and hopeful thing is the encouragement from the vast majority of the community and country in this time of crisis. Despite the airtime that protesters and deniers of the pandemic get, on a daily basis, I only experience responsible citizens that are trying their best to live in this unique time.
OE_other: N/A

OE_upsetting: Having little contact (and no intimacy) with my significant other during and for 14 days after my time on-service in the ICU working with covid patients daily.
OE_positive: More people are showing appreciation and care. To me and to others. At work and outside of work.
OE_other: Based on my work exposure, my ex convinced my son to move from my house to hers. On the one hand, that is sensible and appropriate. Nevertheless, it's one example of the social cost we are all paying to be healthcare workers at this time. In a thousand little ways (and a few big ones) our social web of human nurturing has frayed.

OE_upsetting: Our day to day clinic has not really had any disruptions.  We are calling more patients and screening them before coming into the hospital.  My day as not been that much impacted by this.
OE_positive: People thanking me for being a nurse.  People aware of the risks we take every day to take care of patients.
OE_other: It is amazing how people don't believe in the pandemic and are not following the rules.  They are not wearing mask in public places and will risk other people lives on how they feel.  I think it's a damn if you do and damn if you don't with reopening the country.  There is a huge divide in the country about this.  I don't feel or leader ship has been very supportive on the state or national level.  I feel the safest at the hospital I work in and had very positive communications with Medical director over this.  The communication has been very good and has encourage staff to express our concerns.  We just have to take one day at a time and see what happens.

OE_upsetting: Providing daycare for my 3 kids has been the biggest hurdle.  My parents are retired, but the unease of potentially exposing them is a worry.
OE_positive: Participating in Zoom meetings and Google meets with friends, family, and my kids' classmates.  Everyone needs to feel connected, and it has been great getting to do that even through technology.
OE_other: My job is more behind the scenes, so I work mainly by myself in a back office.  My coworkers have stepped up to fill in where needed to minimize exposure to myself and the patients we care for.  We treat cancer patients, so they are definitely at risk

OE_upsetting: Relentless criticism of national and state efforts to address this crisis by politicians and the national media.
OE_positive: Reliable information and resources from experts in my medical school

OE_upsetting: I can not see my grandkids and my own kids.  It is scary not knowing if you are a carrier of Covid and I do not want to infect my grandkids and children.
OE_positive:
Hy-Vee Grocery store donating items to our hospital for workers-food, hygine products ect.
I felt so appreciated and did not realize that others outside of this he healthcare setting felt so appreciative of our jobs on the front line.

OE_upsetting: Not being able to go on vacation to see family abroad. It was upsetting that the pandemic occurred right as I was about to go on vacation, and I had to readjust my perspective to allow for the current world events and not let that eclipse my personal need for mental rest and wellbeing.
OE_positive: Time to reconnect with nature and reading books has really helped rehabilitate my mental wellbeing

OE_upsetting: I found out that a patient I had prolonged exposure to developed COVID symptoms immediately after and then tested positive for COVID.  I was so worried that I had it and would infect my family.  I moved out of my house for several weeks after that, and I called my sister and made sure she is still ok with taking care of my kids if my husband and I both die.  I feel morally conflicted that I have a duty to take care of patients but that duty is putting my husband and kids at risk, and I have a duty to protect them too.  I can't do both.
OE_positive: My extended family has been calling/facetiming frequently and many have told me specifically how much they support me and love me, which helps me feel less hopeless.
OE_other:
The way these patients get sick and die is depressing and terrifying.  They're so alone, and scared, it's a terrible way for anyone to die. They come in to the ED and they never see their family again.  The last faces they see are obscured by masks and goggles, and the nurses and doctors rarely even go in the room because they're trying to limit their own exposure.  It's heartbreaking.  Many "standard" treatments are denied to these patients because the providers are worried about their own exposure.  I'm morally conflicted about the standard of care the COVID patients receive.   
I spend a lot of time trying to see the big picture, realizing that this will eventually pass and most of us will be ok.  I remind myself that my own chances of severe illness and death, and more importantly those of my immediate family, are low.  Now that I have moved back home, I find joy in the time I get to spend with my family; it is more precious to me for the knowledge that it could all be taken away.  I remind myself how thankful I am that I have a well-paying job and the financial means to come through this epidemic.  And I find comfort in knowing that I can make a difference, I can take care of my patients and find meaning in my work.  I also find it mentally reassuring and stabilizing to go to work and interact with colleagues and not be stuck at home all day; I've been able to retain a modicum of normalcy in going to work every day that many people don't have.  I have severely cut back on my social media use and news consumption to preserve my own mental health.

OE_upsetting: Being unable to see my family and friends. I am living alone for the first time in my life and I feel truly isolated not being able to travel during my time off to go see nearby family and friends.
OE_positive: My research has been approved by the IRB and a national healthcare organization. That part of my career is moving on despite COVID-19.
OE_other: I am pleasantly surprised by the sense of community among healthcare workers.

OE_upsetting:
Fellow nurses showing true colors and selfish personalities.  Refusing to care for Covid-19 patients, out of fear con contracting the virus.  Some medical professionals are covering for weak nursing staff. Whom are using this epidemic as a way to get free vacation. Really hope those professionals realize that they could be doing more to help. Instead of hiding at home.   I have been a nurse 28 years bedside-I love being a nurse-helping others thru difficult times. 
   I volunteered to help-assist in the " Influenza like clinic" (covid test/treatment clinic) but feel abandoned by my management, who seem. pleased to unload nurses to save their budget & exposure to the virus.  
   I miss my co-workers in medical intensive care unit-great teamwork and attitudes.  Pull together and organized to give best evidence-based care to critically ill patients. 

  Really feel isolated and abandoned.
OE_positive: Together with my volunteer medical professions have pulled together a great . Influenza like illness clinic.  Very compassionate and driven to give great care to patients and families.
OE_other: University of Iowa Hospitals and Clinics as done a very good job-of organization of local resources to help the PPE and hand sanitizer.   Pharmacy and Microbiology have kept up with the demand of swabs. And Cedar Ridge Distillery have started making hand.  sanitizer.

OE_upsetting: I would have to say overall it has been the isolation. I work in a rural context and already travel away from home for my practice. During this time I decided it was a duty to work as much as I could while I was healthy and at the same time accept the increased risk of exposure due to increased clinical burden. During that time I was away from my family for an entire month, which is the longest I have been away from them. That was most difficult decision for our family unit.
OE_positive: Actually had a child and was a pleasant reminder that life does and must go on.

OE_upsetting: Watching patients die alone without their families present. Sad.
OE_positive: Having people come help in the hospital to care for patients. Hopeful

OE_upsetting: 2 coworkers in close proximity developed COVID.  Brief fear for myself, but primarily fear for them.  Both have recovered.
OE_positive: Neighborhood kids chalked 'Thank you Doctor Manning and Doctor Hill' on our driveway.  Was during the busiest/hardest time during the outbreak, and it meant a lot.  Still get somewhat emotional thinking about it.

OE_upsetting: nothing
OE_positive: nothing
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Being in the customs line at the airport with 100 other people and not knowing if I was being infected at that time
OE_positive: The support from the community
OE_other: none

OE_upsetting: My mom returning home from out of state to quarantine is the most upsetting thing that has happened to me. I normally live with just my father and we get along great. I don't get along with my mom, so the fact that she traveled back to quarantine with us was incredibly burdensome, especially because she should have stayed put with other family members. She's a very difficult person with mental health issues (depression and alcoholism), so having her in the same house has upped my stress levels on top of all the extra stress of working on a "Covid Floor" at the hospital. I've moved to a room in the basement to be as far away from her as possible (and also to social distance from my parents in general), but it's not enough space to get away from her toxic personality. I tried to find a temporary apartment room, but I don't have the funds to afford it at this time. My other job (non-hospital job) was cut, so my only income is my MICU job, which is only 20 hours a week. Going through a pandemic is hard enough--going through it with her in the house is harder. I wish it wasn't the case, but I can't change things.
OE_positive: I've had more time to delve into home projects because my other job was cut. Lots of home decorating, cooking, baking, and reading! I talk with family members of Covid patients all day on the unit (since visitors aren't allowed in the hospital), so I have a great perspective on how lucky I am to be healthy, have healthy family members, and not feel distanced from what is actually happening with the pandemic. I'm grateful that my family is safe, especially because I've seen a couple Covid deaths over the past month that shed light on how bad this really is/can be.
OE_other: I'm proud to work in the MICU and be a useful member of society during this time. I've only worked on the unit for 6 months, so this is quite an introduction to working in this vein of healthcare. My job has actually been very grounding for me--if I wasn't going in each week and seeing what Covid what actually doing to patients, I might feel more anxious or scared because I wasn't "in the loop" about how the virus affects people. But I am in the loop. I'm there on the floor, able to see the Covid patients with my own eyes and watch the docs and nurses take care of them and help them improve. If I didn't have the stress of my mom living in the house, I think I would be just fine. It's the upheaval of my once-serene home life that has stressed me out, not working in the hospital or fearing contracting the virus myself.

OE_upsetting: Inability to socialize my toddler with other people outside our nuclear family.  I am frustrated that he will have delayed development of his social skills because he has not been able to interact with other children except via FaceTime for the last 2 months.
OE_positive: Ability of hospitalist group to appropriate over-prepare for a surge of patients now unlikely to manifest.

OE_upsetting: That we had to reuse masks in between patient rooms. I wish we had more PPE and that I had to go see COVID patients daily.
OE_positive: That my boyfriend is in isolation with me otherwise I live alone

OE_upsetting: Worry about a patient with multiple neuromuscular issues that contracted COVID in a healthcare setting wouldn't make it. He did well while I was on so I had a little hope but knew based on the timing of his disease this was likely the mild rally we see before declining. I cried that day out of a feeling of hopelessness. He wanted non-invasive ventilation if needed but DNR/DNI and I knew our respiratory therapists were scared of non-invasive ventilation despite everyone wearing a PAPR and being in a negative pressure room and our hospitals official stance that we could use CPAP/BIPAP if there was another reason besides just COVID (such as his neuromuscular disease which we already knew and ICU physicians agreed with this plan). I worked hard to try and go up the chain and directly talk with the respiratory therapists as I felt he would need non-invasive eventually. Found out after I rotated off service he worsened and had to be transferred to another facility as our respiratory therapists wouldn't do it despite all these safeguards. He was facing long term nursing home with or without COVID and had poor outcomes and I had had multiple conversation with him about this but it was sad that he went through a transfer before going hospice though our policy was it was OK to use CPAP/BIPAP in the negative pressure rooms.
OE_positive: Connecting with friends in other states via online chat options because I and they had more down time when not working.
OE_other: I appreciated our hospitalist leadership thinking about our mental health in Feburary and March and as we were ramping up, I was able to say no to volunteering as my husband and I were trying for a child and I was not sure if I was pregnant or not. I grieved for almost a month about the loss of this opportunity because I know as a hospitalist I will be interacting with COVID patients more than most and have decided to delay trying for a child. Its not fair but I feel its the safest option for my husband, myself and any future children I may have. Our state also has laws trying to get rid of abortion and I worry that if I was early in pregnancy, had COVID and terminating the preganancy would save my life that this wouldn't be an option for me which is scary. Due to this pandemic, I am also geographically separated from my in-laws and parents which are both a great sense of support. I have considered that after my contract is up, I will likely move to the same state as my parents as this will help with child care in the future and make even seeing them from a distance more helpful. I would be farther from my in laws but they are adept at using texting and my husband is not quite as close to them as I am with my parents. I have also seen my home state take better public health response to COVID 19 and while I know our hospital took a great stance early, I am quite concerned about our governor opening up the state despite the majority of the state continuing to have outbreaks unlike my home state.

OE_upsetting: Watching the news and the general lack of a unified national response and the lack of consideration by many to not consider others collectively when they make personal choices not to be cautious.
OE_positive: Less people on the streets, less pollution, successful move to telemedicine, quality time with family, and that we learn these lessons and adopt them.
OE_other: I have watched many brave people rise to the occasion and meet the needs of our patients in a selfless and committed manner - it restores my sense of humanity.

OE_upsetting:
I work in Palliative Care and I think the hardest thing has been having family member say over the phone “I’ll never get over not being with my mother when she dies.”
I felt helpless and sad as I felt being with my own mother when she died was a gift.
OE_positive: We had a influx of patients of Hispanic culture and the families were so appreciative of everything we were doing and acknowledged this on every phone call. This seemed very meaningful to me.
OE_other: I’m not sure anything could have prepared me for this.

OE_upsetting: - worries about financing as I do not know what it is going to happen in the financials of our hospital
OE_positive: self quarantine --> gave me a lot time for myself(usually I spent that with my kids) and I finished a lot work
OE_other: I had less pulmonary clinics but I had to cover in the ICU (not a lot) but to reduce the workload of those were assigned to ICU the last month

OE_upsetting: The fact that policies and procedures have been implemented that hinder physicians ability to provide care by people not directly involved in patient care and without anyone’s consultation that does patient care
OE_positive: The fact that we successfully extubated our second ever COVID patient and she was able to be discharged to home

OE_upsetting: Faculty meeting where the researchers contributions were lauded over and over again and not a single clinician was even acknowledged.
OE_positive: My family has taken my concerns seriously and completely isolated themselves at home.  It has given me one less thing to worry about,
OE_other: There is no recognition of how hard ID doctors are working and there's no release valve.  Everyone just expects everyone to give more and they offer webinars on wellness or virtual happy hours - but this is just one more thing to do when nobody already has any extra time.  There needs to be protected time.   There has also been a more than usual bias against single people -- assuming we can just work more because we have no childcare responsibilities or don't need a day off.  We are socially isolated because we don't live with a spouse or children and those effects don't seem to come into play at all when deciding who needs a day off.

OE_upsetting: Having friends and family not take the pandemic seriously is upsetting. I am telling family members daily that their loved one has died alone in a hospital room. Seeing them go about their daily lives without masks or consideration for those who they might kill, or that they might get sick themselves, is infuriating. This, and the general state of the country at large make it difficult to keep my morale up. It feels like drowning.
OE_positive: My friend had a baby a few days ago, and luckily the whole family is healthy and well. It may be cliche, but seeing a new person in the world gives me hope, and motivation to try to make this situation the best it can be, so this child has a great place to grow.
OE_other: I want everyone to understand that there is a component of this situation that was entirely avoidable. Racial inequity and structural inequality that prevent people from obtaining preventative care have led to populations being disproportionately affected by chronic disease, which makes them more vulnerable to COVID 19. Additionally, had the federal government responded appropriately or even competently, this situation would have been less severe. As someone with an MD/MPH, it makes me want to scream.

OE_upsetting: Not letting my child see her cousins/grandparents
OE_positive: New projects/responsibilities at work
OE_other: Exhausting, sad

OE_upsetting: My friends are too worried and practice  unreasonable avoidance behaviors
OE_positive: I learned that I’m braver and more determined to serve in capacity of medical worker than many others
OE_other: I don’t see us being heroes, we are doing a job we chose by our free will and taking care of COVID pts is just one of the many obligations we accepted by being health care workers

OE_upsetting: Been unable to see my family and friends. It makes me sad because I don't know when that will change.
OE_positive: Feel closer and supported by my coworkers.

OE_upsetting: Patient coding during intubation, she was only 52, obese, difficulty to oxygenate and ventilate, lost my visor during CPR, got her back and intubated, but was definitely exposed. Got sick with COVID 5 days later, infected my husband despite quarantining
OE_positive: My daughter came home because college is closed. I miss her and it gives me more purpose to have her around
OE_other: Profits should not be driving resource allocation, health care delivery, testing, etc. This has highlighted how morally corrupt our health care system is. Administrators allow physicians to be the fall guy. Patients suffer, physicians are not protected, and the government stands by and says it's not their responsibility. When need to legislate change, national coverage for all.

OE_upsetting: i really have not had anything personally happen to me.
OE_positive: met new people when i was sent to the remote testing site
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Death of a friend who had COVID 19. It is very upsetting, mostly because he was quite ill for at least 6 weeks. I never had the opportunity to visit him.
OE_positive: Reconnecting with neighbors. Made me feel very cared for and supported. Also made me feel very fortunate for their presence.
OE_other: It has become much easier relatively quickly in my setting. The local government response and the hospital response have made me feel very hopeful and supported. The first few weeks were challenging because we were behind the curve in New Orleans with a very significant outbreak. Those were scary days. It’s much better now, but I am not enjoying practicing Medicine as much with having to wear all the PPE. I know it’s necessary, but it makes my interactions with patients feel very impersonal.

OE_upsetting: 1) That I can't hug my mom. That my mom and dad can't hug my daughter. 2) Before we learned how much sedation was needed, patients were coming back up from the unit telling up things they remembered - like being intubated, having a rectal tube placed. That was tough.
OE_positive: That remdesivir shows modest improvement. That my hospital has EUA doses.  That the IL-antagonists show some benefit. It is all only a glimmer of hope, but I'll take anything. Knowing that there are things that might improve outcomes helps keep me calmer. Oh and all the thanks from everyone. I'm not really doing anything that special - its the floor nurses on COVID units that deserve our utmost thanks and appreciation
OE_other: It has been interesting, socially, to see how my colleagues deal with stress.

OE_upsetting: My aunt was ill at the start of one week, her health declined and within days she had passed away so quickly/suddenly from suspected COVID-19. It made me very upset and unable to process the loss or grieve due to stay at home orders and being overworked.
OE_positive: I have been on a trying to conceive/fertility journey since the end of last year. It was put on hold due to COVID-19, but will be starting the process back up. I am hopeful that while COVID-19 is not going away, I will be able to start a family.
OE_other: With hospitals looking to have a resurgence while a pandemic is ongoing may not seem like the best idea. Outpatient practices are short staffed and you are now putting the staff at risk. Also, creating a larger workload then before while being overwhelmed with the anxieties of this pandemic is detrimental to one's mental health.

OE_upsetting:
My husband recently accepted a new job in a different state (which was a very difficult decision and I am feeling incredibly sad about moving). He had to delay his move (which I am happy about) but I know once the pandemic slows down he will move and I will follow about 1 year later due to training. I have still been experiencing a lot of grief associated with this move, even though I am happy he has found his 'dream job.' 

This had nothing to do with COVID-19, just happened at the same time of the pandemic. But it has been a difficult issue for both of us.
OE_positive: Been able to spend a lot more time outside doing activities I have enjoyed since early in the pandemic my work days were shortened (when all elective procedures were canceled and the hospital was empty). The hospital census has now returned to a more normal level so my work hours are back to pre-pandemic hours. But it has been good to enjoy more time outdoors. Its also very hopeful to see communities band together to support local restaurants and people have put up yard-signs to encourage each other.
OE_other: Our hospital was well prepared, kept the staff updated, and acted in a timely manor. Our staff has been safe and everyone has worked well together. It has been an honor to serve my community by coming to work, even if for the most part I have not cared for those with Covid.

OE_upsetting: In the beginning, our administration was ruling that nurses would be fired if they were caught wearing masks in a non covid unit.  I was screening people for symptoms and travel history along with temp checks in the front of the cancer center and I remember thinking I was going to get fired for wearing a mask.  That moment caused me to rethink my entire career and future plans.  The sheer idiocy of the statement and knowing that it was directly related to the lack of preparedness caused emotions that I still can't describe.
OE_positive: I had a mental breakdown of sorts within the first few weeks and my co-workers gave me a card and some 'happy's' to cheer me up.
OE_other: Nothing else.   Thank you for allowing me to participate in this study.

OE_upsetting: I have not been that upset.
OE_positive: I've managed to set up teleconferencing.  It gave me a sense of mastery.  I feel confident I can expand these skills into doing telebehavioral health if I need to.
OE_other: I rarely work in the hospital proper.  I am wondering if you should have excluded me.

OE_upsetting: Not being able to go to new york with my mother for her birthday and mother's day. Made me very depressed to not be able to spend the time with her.
OE_positive: I've saved lots of money by not being able to vacation.

OE_upsetting: Seeing a child pass away from COVID and watching mom's grief - made me feel helpless
OE_positive: Receiving food from local restaurants at the hospital - makes me feel appreciated

OE_upsetting: Basically everything fun that was supposed to happen in 2020 has been cancelled for me.  Including but not limited to: my bachelorette party which fell on my birthday, any birthday celebrations with my family, my wedding shower, my fiance's bachelor party, my wedding, and the honeymoon i was soooo looking forward to.  I'm now left with 3 weeks of vacation I cannot give back, so they're pretty much wasted.
OE_positive: I've had friends and family rally around me to support me and show appreciation for my work.  I've been thrown virtual bachelorettes, been sent countless cards and gifts, had people enter me into contests, and my friends check on me very regularly.  It has made me feel very loved.
OE_other: My effective coping skills have been spending time in nature with my dog and lots of cuddling with the dog.

OE_upsetting: While on nights, making a non-COVID patient with respiratory distress comfort care who was DNR/DNI. I did not know the patient well and felt it was difficult to walk the family through the decision to pursue comfort care overnight without knowing the patient very well.
OE_positive: Spending more time with my niece and nephew.

OE_upsetting: I am most upset by cancellation of activities that I used to enjoy such as swimming and music. I understand why they had to be cancelled and know they will eventually restart but I find it frustrating and disappointing.
OE_positive: I have been able to spend time cultivating friendships, even though it is happening remotely.
OE_other: It has overall been a positive experience. There is much less arguing about the common, minor problems and annoyances.

OE_upsetting: Managing staff who were scared to come to work because they feared infecting their family - some of whom had serious medical conditions.  I felt anxious and overwhelmed.
OE_positive: Support from colleagues and the community.  #middlesexstrong  I felt that my work was meaningful.

OE_upsetting: taking care of COVID patients with reusing PPE.  No PPE supplies.  Feel vulnerable and defenseless
OE_positive: Supportive fellow staff
OE_other: non-compliant public increases stress level

OE_upsetting: Feeling as though my supervisor has not been open or sensitive to feedback about current workload and equal sharing of work among our team.
OE_positive: We are closer to summer and can do so much more outside

OE_upsetting: Feeling burned out from quadrupling my workload
OE_positive: Seeing the support of my colleagues has been outstanding and made me feel uplifted

OE_upsetting: stress over how to deal with nervous physicians and staff who have a louder and higher level of worry than I do
OE_positive: appreciate the responsibility given me to help organize and interpret
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Seeing patients be upset or afraid because they aren’t able to have a loved one with them in the clinic/hospital while they’re there. I feel sad for them, it must be quite scary having to be alone, you lose a sense of security not having someone there with you.
OE_positive: Being able to work as a team along with other departments/disciplines in the hospital and coming together to come up with great plans. We’ve now formed great relationships with other departments that has made us stronger now and will continue to benefit us into the future.

OE_upsetting: Seeing people in my community without jobs. My heart aches for them. I have a job and don't have to worry about feeding my family.
OE_positive: Seeing my family at home each and every day. They are more relaxed, helping around the house, and appreciate the work I do for others.
OE_other: Perspective is everything.

OE_upsetting: Increase in unsafe activities around my home (not in hospital community) including attempted break-ins, car roberies, a neighbor's house being struck by likely and a homicide in my area. These happened in a short period of time and have increased my anxiety both at home and while in the community/work, being more on edge, impacted sleep/headaches
OE_positive: I have an amazingly supportive team so I am thankful to continue to be going in to work on my regular schedule for their support, as well as the sense of normalcy
OE_other: I am thankful at Middlesex that we have received regular communication from our immediate supervisor and director, but also from higher levels, including the hospital CEO. I think that our community has made an effort to work together and support one another, as well as to focus on positives and good things that are happening

OE_upsetting: The hardest thing has been NOT seeing family because I don' t know if I've been exposed to the virus thru co-workers or patients (before telemed was implemented) and I am afraid to pass it on to them. I live alone and I have not visited my family since February. Although we took a chance this Tuesday, since the state is opening up, but we were outside and I wore a mask. The other thing that is upsetting: Is this serious or not??? It feels words are said but actions are done in the opposite. Worry but don't worry.
OE_positive: I am doing yoga telemed that I would never haave had the time to do before.
OE_other: I wish management would share more about their views of this and what they think is happening about the information. Just numbers don't do it for me.

OE_upsetting: chest compressions and feeling and hearing ribs breaking.
OE_positive: Working at a higher level of care. I enjoy the challenge
OE_other: Would never want to go through anything like this again

OE_upsetting: Although I now work via telehealth with child clients, I worked in our behavioral health offices for some weeks and go there now on occasion.  I am quarantined from my daughter, a college student, and only saw her 3 hours, with precautions, on Mother's Day; I am distraught but totally committed to my clients.
OE_positive: Maintaining the connection with my clients, in this case virtually.  This has been easier with the older clients but parents are very supportive also in staying in the sessions with the younger clients.  Clients fluctuate in terms of emotions and behaviors given so many changes and losses they are experiencing,  But I feel so satisfied being with my clients when they need us the most.
OE_other: It's tough.  I am reminded of the destruction of my native Nicaragua during war.  I am reminded of the aftermath of Sandy Hook since I was a school principal in New Haven.  I worry about standing when the ground is shaking.  But the communication from our state, hospital and Behavioral Health Department has been superb. And the level of commitment from all of us is extraordinary.

OE_upsetting: Having to argue with nursing to get an N95 mask for a covid positive patient on airborne precautions. I ended up using an used N95 from a colleague.
OE_positive: The support from patients - their gratitude.
OE_other: It has been hard, but I am hopeful for better days ahead and for us all to realize the healthcare system needs to be better.

OE_upsetting: I am very lucky because I am a behavioral health intern and currently working from home.  I was told last week that the hospital may have us come back to work in the office not because any decline in COVID19 cases has occurred at our hospital, but because of the optics.  I was also told by our clinic manager that our ability to work from home (which is what has most helped me cope with my anxiety) will depend in large part on how long insurance is willing to pay for our services to be from home instead of facility-based.  My husband is a Navy psychologist so he is working with patients in-person at the Navy hospital every day still and could be deployed if this becomes more severe.  I worry that between my husband seeing patients and my potentially needing to return to the office, that our children are far more likely to get COVID19 and that we will need to resort to childcare options that will further increase their exposure simply because our friends and family are too afraid to be near us since my husband sees patients in-person.  We do not have any friends or family who are NOT working from home at this time.  I worry that I will need to choose between starting my postdoc in September or keeping my family safe as waves of this virus continue due to poor national responses to this pandemic.  I do not want to put my children at risk just so I can go to work when I am working effectively from home.  My attendance rate and productivity (and effectiveness) have actually increased working from home (because I'm putting in a lot more effort and hours to justify working from home) and I feel taken for granted, hurt, vulnerable, and angry that on top of being apart from all my family and friends, missing graduation and in-person defense of my PhD, and cancelling our first vacation in years as a family, the VP and higher up management of the hospital could put my health at risk simply because they feel it would look better for us to all be in the office or because one or
OE_positive: I have felt tremendous gratitude to be able to work from home at this time.  I feel fortunate for job security and the opportunity to finally finish my degree so, despite lockdown, I can still move on professionally and provide for my family.  While I am upset with the highest up management at the hospital, I love my coworkers, supervisor, and clinic manager and I am very grateful for them. <3  I'm grateful for our home, nice neighborhood, and big lawn so quarantine does not feel that limiting.
OE_other: I would love to see more healthcare professionals in upper management.  Our upper management is primarily MBAs so the financial end of things is their focus.  They then make decisions about how to best weather a pandemic without the science background that the rest of us have.  We are all mindful of the science behind this pandemic and that informs our concerns and how we want to work and interact with patients.  Having someone who does not honor the scientific realities at play but controls what is expected of me as an employee during this pandemic makes me feel taken advantage of, vulnerable, and scared. That said, our clinic management is amazing and we have taken extra care to provide mental health support groups for healthcare workers and their children as well as provide more "team huddles" on Zoom for us to congregate as a clinic, shoot the sh!t, and support one another.  It makes me feel like I am not alone as I go through this working from my little home office.  I am also SO grateful to have a home office so I can work in a quiet, secure place that ensures confidentiality.  I have some colleagues who are going into the office because they do not feel comfortable offering services from home given a lack of quiet office space. Thank you for conducting this study! I hope it goes well!

OE_upsetting: That the majority of the consulting services refuse to do their jobs because of covid. I had a patient with a STEMI die because he was not intervened upon. The number of hours I spend on the phone fighting with consulting services to provide basic care to these patients is unreal and frankly disgusting.
OE_positive: Nothing positive has happened
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Hearing that people I know have died.
OE_positive: Observing the best in so many people who go to work and take care of very sick people even though it is dangerous.
OE_other: I am so proud of all the health care and support workers.

OE_upsetting: Colleague became very sick, ICU for over a month, discharged to SNF on a vent with a trach.. Terribly sad for him, his partner and family.
OE_positive: Friends bringing by dinner, or sending dessert, when they know I have been in clinic/testing tent all day
OE_other: I do worry about not having enough PPE as an outpatient doctor. When we are in a room with possible COVID+ patients, it's a 20 minute personal interaction. Outpatient doctors need as much protection as people on inpatient service.  And Trump is an ass.

OE_upsetting: n/a
OE_positive: n/a
OE_other: n/a

OE_upsetting: Trying to conduct psychotherapy with telehealth. It has been very difficult to connect with people. I have had many technical problems. Sessions seem superficial. I cannot properly assess people on a little screen. I've never felt so ineffectual as a therapist.
OE_positive: I have been able to keep working and provide for my family.
OE_other: no

OE_upsetting: Early on feeling helpless as people were not talking risks seriously
OE_positive: Working from home with my 2 and 4 year olds- having “tea” time scheduled

OE_upsetting: My 11 year old son broke down crying because he was concerned about my wife and myself because we are both doctors and might get exposed /sick, he was tired of hearing about COVID "everywhere", and he felt like "everyday was the same" from being stuck at home.  It made me sad that he was dealing with this and that despite my efforts to help him, my other responsibilities meant that I didn't do enough.
OE_positive: Several of my neighbors have ordered a family dinner or given me a restaurant gift card because they knew I was a ED doctor and dealing with the outbreak. It definitely made me feel appreciated for the work I do and risk I take.

OE_upsetting: My yoga studio closed and my hairdresser closed and this makes me depressed and ugly.
OE_positive: I went to Dunkin Doughnuts to  pick up a 'box of joe' for a coworker celebration and the staff thanked me for "doing the job that you do."
OE_other: If this is the 'richest country' then why aren't we prepared?  why don't we have enough PPE?

OE_upsetting: I was assigned to perform a 1 hour online assessment on a patient who was highly agitated, hostile, and talked about having guns and having thoughts of shooting himself.  I tried contacting my supervisor but did not get a response.  It made me feel afraid and powerless,
OE_positive: I've heard patients express more gratitude for family and the help they are receiving.

OE_upsetting: That the children are not allowed to go back to school especially when looking at the low mortality rate of covid to people in connecticut under the age of 69...this age protects not just children but the kids. OE_other: I feel bad for all of the people being furloughed and its a shame that the govenors didnt have more PPE for the medical staff. I would laos like to thank the laundry, housecleaners,  and janitors.

OE_positive: better and more often interaction with friends

OE_upsetting: I considered committing suicide, but talked to my psychiatrist and husband,  am now on medication and increased therapy and am doing well
OE_positive: my 9-month old child is safe and has no idea what's going on,and I have been able to continue to be a good mother to him.

OE_upsetting:
My family avoiding me due to my work responsibilities
 makes me feel lonely/left out

People banning together to help in any way shape or form

OE_positive: The increased use of technology to keep people informed, such as ZOOM.

OE_upsetting: Leaving my children and husband and living apart from them for the past 6+ weeks because I work everyday at the hospital and often with COVID patients. My toddler daughter now prefers other family members to me. It made me feel incredibly depressed and like I wanted to die.

OE_upsetting: Being told not to do CPR because of COVId status. I don’t feel like a doctor.

OE_upsetting: I work on a COVID ICU unit. The majority of our patients are COVID positive. Other floors are considered clean units and do not accept COVID patients. All nurses in this hospital are getting the same pay regardless of contact with COVID patients. I think the floors that are working directly with COVID patients need to get hazard pay considering we are at risk and putting ourselves on the line each and every day we are at work.
OE_other: I worry about transmitting it to my loved ones. I also think that it is unacceptable that we are not able to use a new N95 mask for every COVID patient.

OE_upsetting: Realizing that my children's lives with changed and limited by social distancing for considerably longer than I originally thought. This is giving me anxiety and sadness.
OE_positive: My leadership team at work has really pulled together to get us through this. Hopeful.

OE_upsetting: Having to postpone my wedding for a year. It makes me feel safe and frustrated at time because I have to delay an aspect of my life that was important to me and it is completely out of my control.
OE_positive: Being able to spend more time with my finacee and grow closer to one another. Exploring other hobbies and interests together.

OE_positive: I don’t know.
OE_other: It’s only getting harder with outpatient elective procedures reopening. Our covid numbers and coverage needs Havent gone down so we (cardiology fellows) are now just stretched thinner.

OE_upsetting: There is not enough PPE, leadership (nurse manager) says we need to reuse our supplies until visibly soiled and that is disgusting. As a result, masks smell moldy. They change policies daily and don't put it in writing as they don't want to be sued. Poor leadership/lack of it has been a real struggle.
OE_positive: My staff friends have been there for me. Getting closer to a few of the good staff members.
OE_other: It is awful. I would not recommend it. The outside world (society) respects us, but manager just wants to work us into the ground. I'm supposed to have 6 patients and I normally have 9-14 now because of the pandemic and so many coworker catching COVID. Very frustrating that no new staff is hired because who wants to work here with COVID, and people are quitting. It is a mess. Someone needs to better regulate what is going on here. We need a union for the workers, because I KNOW we are being taken advantage of.

OE_upsetting: My wife left me out of fear of getting the virus because I work in the hospital. I am lonely.
OE_positive: I have a new girlfriend and we talk every day. She makes me feel special.
OE_other: It’s the same but now everyone wears masks.

OE_upsetting: I have been recently divorced as a single mom trying to balance work in a unsteady environment and help my 11 yo with distance learning has been a huge challenge - this has increased my stress level overall
OE_positive: I have taken care of 2 positive covid OB patients and the outcome for mom and baby were great and they were discharged to home safe and well-this made me feel great that I was able to provide the same great care (despite looking like im going to the moon with all the PPE on)
OE_other: I feel so badly for the patients that have lost their lives and have not had family at their side. My good friend lost her dad to covid, he was in a nursing home in branford CT, I feel its so sad that family cant have closure in saying goodbye at the bedside

OE_upsetting: Speaking to the families of COVID icu patients and knowing they are likely never going to see/hug/kiss their loved one ever again and that I am their lifeline to the patient.
OE_positive: Working on a COVID unit that is a surge unit and having all of the random providers come together and work hard as a team.

OE_upsetting: commutation between management and staff. We have got instructions but they are never clear and change every few days. This gives me horrible anxiety and I'm going on 3 weeks with a constant headache because my blood press is up from the stress.
OE_positive: nothing happened to me but its nice to see communities and people giving eachother hope. its uplifting

OE_upsetting: Seeing patients suffering alone, no family to visit. Having them pass alone with no family by their side.

OE_upsetting: Since I don't live with my parents and they are in the at risk category due to their age, I  haven't been able to see them in person very much due to the potential risk that I could pose to them. This made Easter and Mother's Day slightly depressing.
OE_positive: I think the change in weather has been helpful for my spirits. Just seeing the sun and having the increase in temperature has made the situation more bearable. Also UPMC offered online virtual fitness classes that have been amazing and have helped to keep me positive.
OE_other: I work in an outpatient clinic that is attached to a hospital, so I've pretty much only been indirectly affected by the pandemic. But the terrible situations do exist and just because I don't see them on a day to day basis does not mean that they aren't happening elsewhere.

OE_upsetting: Cannot visit elderly grandparents. Sad to see them lonely.
OE_positive: Have been able to spend much more time with my young children.

OE_upsetting: We had a death in our family and could not be there for other family members and we had a brother diagnosed with Cancer and we cannot be there for him.  I feel sad and feel like a terrible sister since I cannot assist my bother and his family
OE_positive: the birth of a great granson
OE_other: Our hospital has keep us informed of all the necessary information need every day during this pandemic

OE_upsetting: My husband was unable to attend the anatomy ultrasound for our first pregnancy. I was anxious and less excited about the experience without his support.
OE_positive: It is hopeful to see the initiatives and support provided to those affected by the pandemic.

OE_upsetting: The first time I was preparing to work with COVID-19 patients, I called the employee hotline to discuss what I could do to reduce the risk of bringing it home to my husband and young son who I can not isolate myself from. The person I spoke with provided absolutely no support and basically told me that there was nothing I could do. I am waiting 2 weeks from being in a COVID+ room before seeing my parents to ensure none of us in the house can pass it on to them inadvertently. They are both unwell and at high risk of getting ill. As such, despite living 10 minutes away, my parents have not seen any of us in person in over 2 months.
OE_positive: Many of the patients I have worked with on the COVID+ units are not COVID- and getting  better on rehab. It's been a joy to see them get better and hopefully home to their own families soon.
OE_other: I'm not sure what we can do to help the public understand that this isn't a hoax or some type of conspiracy towards them. It's serious. I think that's the most frustrating part.

OE_upsetting: The unknown regarding the pandemic and relative lack of knowledge/preparedness initially
OE_positive: Sense of community between my colleagues and family

OE_upsetting: Upset that my high school senior's graduation related events have been moved to virtual and the actual ceremony moved to end of July. Concern about whether there will be online "remote" start to college in the fall. Disappointed for her. And the uncertainty of whether my current employer will make any faculty/staff cuts given the current financial situation as other institutions have done and how this will affect my faculty group.
OE_positive: Great teamwork with our group

OE_upsetting: I haven't had any upsetting events happen to me.
OE_positive: More private family time since we can't do anything else right now

OE_upsetting: not feeling like my concerns for the staffs safety were actually heard or addressed
OE_positive: Started working form home part time and it made me feel happy and relieved

OE_upsetting: Grandpa's dying in an ICU bed because his meat packaging plant stayed open without testing employees. 30% of the staff has tested positive for covid. Confirms with me that the system is fundamentally flawed.
OE_positive: Work from home every other day has made me realize that this is all theater and our jobs can be completely performed in this way year round, but for some reason ($) they aren't.

OE_positive: easter
