OE_upsetting:
I was present the night a co-worker physically assaulted another co-worker disagreeing over a nursing call. The co-worker who attacked has a history of lashing out. She verbally lashed out at me after the assault. The co-worker who was assaulted took 3 months medical leave to cope with the mental and physical trauma. The co-worker who assaulted her was allowed to return to work within two days.

The assaulting co-worker a month or so later mocked a patient in report for their gender identity and sexual orientation. When I defended the patient, the co-worker asked me to disclose my own gender identity and sexual orientation, attempting to gain ground for laughing at the patient, who identified as a demi-boy. I'm pansexual.

In both the physical assault and the verbal attacks, my managers defended the offending person, and ignored the incidents. I feel afraid. I can't trust my managers. Depending on the night, I fear for my safety and my patients'. Trying to keep others safe in the pandemic, I feel deeply isolated. I miss my friends and my supports.
OE_positive:
On Thanksgiving, my spouse's family had a bonfire outside with safe social distancing at my request. I work midnights and have been struggling a lot with the loneliness and lack of sleep.

My nieflings and in-laws filled a book with encouraging notes for me. I felt seen and loved and wanted. It was the first time in a long time I didn't feel like an outcast, and I felt like I wasn't alone or stuck in the vacuum of covering shifts, impossible nights, and medical personnel isolation.
OE_other: I'm burned out. I'm lonely. I miss other humans so much. It hurts when I see people not following safety guidelines, because I've given up so much for their wellbeing, and if they would have just tried for a little while to isolate, health care workers wouldn't be stuck in this hell.

OE_other: Childcare is the main problem. When kids have a runny nose, they get kicked out of daycare for days, and there is no one that can help with childcare. And as an essential worker, I'm still expected to go to work. So there is no possible solution to the problem. It's extremely frustrating, nerve-wracking, and it keeps me up at night.
There are no words to describe the continued death of our patients and incompetency of our government. The stress is overwhelming and these experiences are one that we will never forget.

OE_upsetting: Multiple people were let go from their jobs within my department, and multiple, close coworkers have suffered additional losses in their families. Not only has it created more work for less people, but I also feel more sadness throughout each day for myself, family, and friends.

OE_positive: Since May, 2020, I was hired into a new population health role at work with comes with some salary support. This made me feel motivated and valued.

Watching a mob of White supremacist vigilantes march down my street (while shielding my child from seeing it) to go attack BLM activists who were peacefully protesting. It hurts.
OE_positive: The COVID vaccine!!!!!!! I got it a little over a week ago and it gives me HOPE that things will get better eventually, not soon, but eventually. Maybe next year I'll be able to see my show family for the holidays if we're all vaccinated!

My brother's wife refused to let my family visit this fall with her or my nephews due to COVID concerns despite us taking precautions AND she allowed her own sister to visit (clear double standard). I believe everyone can agree that COVID-19 is an ugly monster that has destroyed many family by taking lives, however, if we are going to take anything positive from this catastrophe, people are more focused on what's important to them, health, family and friends.  We, as a people, are appreciating the smaller (as well as larger things) we took for granted a year ago.

OE_upsetting: Being isolated.  My college daughter, who spends time between her father and I, spent more time with her father since I was working at the hospital and her father does not work and is home.  It was a mutual decision to protect her and also her father who has health issues; he was diagnosed with Covid-19 but has recuperated.  Unfortunately, I also lost my beloved dogs, my companions, one in September and one in November.  That has been very difficult.
OE_positive: Weekly Zoom meetings with my family, in CA, PR, NY and CT which has brought us even closer.  I also began to see some of my young clients in person in the past few weeks, rather than virtually, and that has really kept be grounded.
OE_other: My department has made great effort to keep us connected (virtually), motivated, and even amused.

OE_upsetting: Having a young patient with 5 kids die. Made me feel inadequate and question my management decisions, even though I went over every decision for that patient in extra detail.
OE_positive: Seeing my kids learn new things. Make me feel free of the world we are living in, and of my relentless yet ineffective efforts to change it.
OE_other: Thank you for your efforts to document the effects on providers. Many of the things we feel aren't so different from our everyday practice in critical care, but because we are thinking and hearing about these experiences everywhere (media, friends, hospital communications, etc) and all the time, they are no longer compartmentalized, and I think that contributes to an emotional burnout in a major way.

OE_positive: Seeing folks getting the vaccine and be excited about it has been really hopeful. Getting my vaccine and encouraging others has made me feel grateful

OE_upsetting: My coworker wouldn't consistently wear his mask in our office
OE_positive: I got my vaccination yesterday!  I feel hopeful that things will improve.

OE_upsetting: The surgeon reporting me to my program director. I've always been someone who gets very positive feedback for my interpersonal relationships, especially those I build with patients, so it was a slap in the face for someone to tell my boss that I'm rude, and worse, for the story to be corroborated by a colleague.
OE_positive: Getting offered my top choice job. It was such a good feeling to know that my training is finally coming to an end and it has all been worth it, helping me to secure exactly the position I want at this point in my life.
OE_other: I spent the worst of the pandemic in residency at an institution in NYC, so this survey may not be as relevant given different (frankly, more positive) experiences that I had there.

Getting my vaccine!

OE_upsetting: Misinformation related to the COVID19 pandemic and the response from those who felt that we, as healthcare providers, are stealing from them and exaggerating the pandemic has been the most hurtful. OE_other: We aren't just tired but emotionally and physically depleted to a point where I don't know when we will be whole again. OE_upsetting: Getting COVID in spite of being SO careful. It makes me feel like a failure, and like a poor example to everyone I know. Especially since I tested positive after getting the first dose of my vaccine. I worry that others will distrust the vaccine knowing that I tested positive in between doses (even though that’s not based in science). It is exhausting to constantly have to be an example of how to behave in this pandemic.
OE_positive: Getting the first dose of my Covid vaccine. It filled me with hope and gratitude to all who have been working tirelessly in this pandemic as well as to the patients who’ve allowed me the privilege of their care.
OE_other: The resources my hospital has put in place to ensure that we are not overburdened with work by sticking to service caps and not adding extra service weeks is tremendous. The fact that we did not receive a pay cut as many of our peers did across the country is very much appreciated.
It has been disheartening to have to deal with the medical and political side of all of this. President Trump’s horrific response to the pandemic has directly caused death, burnout, and exhaustion

OE_upsetting:
At one point during the pandemic my girlfriend suddenly got a fever. We live together. She works from home. I immediately thought it could be COVID, and that I was the most likely person that spread it to her. It was a panic moment for me and a worst case scenario. We had agreed to continue to live together in the same room at the beginning of the pandemic and I knew something like this could happen.
As it turned out, we both got tested for COVID and our tests were negative. Still, thinking I gave a loved one COVID was deeply upsetting psychologically and stressed me out deeply.
OE_positive: One of my patients with severe COVID had an incredible recovery and then was featured on the local news and I also was interviewed and was on the news. This was a really special, hard-working, determined patient and I was honored to have been a part of her care and to have been one of a large team that supported her on her path toward recovery.

OE_upsetting: I began having panic attacks at the end of October. I felt scared, ashamed, and out of control. I live in a good neighborhood, but I feel myself becoming more suspicious of others and getting scared of what they might do. I feel powerless. I started seeing a therapist who was trying to give me strategies to prevent and resolve panic attacks, but I often need help from my partner which makes me feel helpless because I can't even control my emotions. I worry that having these issues will keep me from being a good doctor in the future.
OE_positive: I got an interview for medical school admission at a place I would really like to attend. I am still very nervous about it, but it is a sign to myself that I probably won't be stuck in this situation for much longer. Even if I don't get into this school or any of the other schools on my list this year, I feel better knowing that I took these steps, especially during a pandemic. It's a sign to myself that my life is still moving despite being in quarantine for almost a year, which is hopeful and profoundly strange because sometimes applying during quarantine feels like I'm stuck on the bottom of a river and the current is moving above me. Getting this interview is a sign that I might be swept up and continue moving, something I'm very grateful for.
OE_other: This pandemic has exacerbated problems that have existed in society for a while and shown us what people are willing to do to help their neighbors, and I am incredibly disappointed with what I'm seeing. Frankly though, I'm tired of trying to explain science and compassion to those who will not listen. I'm just so profoundly tired.

OE_upsetting: Health issues with my elderly parents. My mom is developing dementia. They live across the country and have little support. We are semi-estranged but they relay on me for assistance with their healthcare. I feel helpless.
OE_positive: My family is healthy and my daughter is able to go to preschool. I feel grateful.

OE_upsetting: Just feeling stressed and not having ability to drink water, use bathroom or have time for lunch. Just want to be a normal human being with basic "rights". I felt very sad and unfortunately broke down in front of my staff.
OE_positive: Vaccine coming out, hopeful I will be able to go away on vacation at certain point.

OE_positive: I became pregnant with my first child. Makes me feel excited but also anxious.

OE_positive: vaccine being rolled out. happy, relieved, hopeful.

My personal life is just fine. I’m just very worried about the state of our democracy.
OE_positive: Biden/Harris election. Hope their administration will also usher in some rational public health policies, especially with respect to covid, but regarding health care in general.

OE_upsetting:
Not enough PPE has been a huge concern.  My daughter, a nurse called and shared that the hospital was out of PPE and they planned to send her in Covid rooms without PPE.  Thanks to amazing donations staff were provided but must reuse PPE and masks.

My father fell and broke his hip, he was sent home without proper care, he returned two more times to the hospital before he received treatment.  Because of the fall has cognitive issues. The doctor put in an order for family to be present, we were denied access and my father suffered.  My father contracted Covid in the hospital as he shared staff took of there masks to eat.  There are so many secondary concerns.  
We have many other concerns:  While caring for a dying patient with Covid the family was not permitted to visit until he passed. Heart breaking.  Family can not support patients and staff are asked too much.

OE_upsetting:
Being so prepared during the entirety of my medical education to cram down my thoughts and feelings about institutional racism and the prejudice I am bound to experience over the course of my training, just to turn around and watch institution after institution decide to “wake up” and acknowledge racism in this country because of the gruesome murder of George Floyd. But there were so many before Floyd. And issuing a statement and “promising to be better going forward” does little to acknowledge each institutions complicity before that sentinel event, OR to admit just how unprepared they were to change the micro cultures that are still going to exist despite the C suites (in healthcare and all other fields) sending out a PR email saying Black Lives Matter. So it makes it HARDER to seek accountability because now institutions can say “wait, whoa whoa we’re doing something. What do you mean we are still racist.” So I’ve dealt with a lot of the feelings of anger due to what feels like a cop-out and quick, easy “fix” to a problem that existed long before 2020 and will continue to exist. 

The most upsetting part is that being a “silent radical” as I call it (keeping one’s head down to get THROUGH the parts where how one is perceived determines one’s success in their career) seems to not be enough anymore, though I doubt institutions are actually ready for us to be vocal with all of our grievances because they are numerous, we just remain silent about them because the few that we do determine are bad enough to bring forth aren’t even fully rectified, so it seems like there aren’t many more where those few came from. We just knew it was a moot point, and the sad thing is they’re still going to be a moot point because at the end of the day institutions aren’t REALLY ready to change. They don’t even know what that change would entail.
OE_positive: Being accepted and nurtured by a majority of the colleagues in the specialty of choice I am pursuing as an MS4
OE_other: I wanted to also include that it was very upsetting that, once the numbers started to show that black and brown people were over represented in the COVID mortality rate, it felt like THAT was when the majority of white anti-maskers determined they didn’t have to wear a mask or adhere to social distancing precautions, because it wasn’t as bad for them or their loved ones. The disproportionate number of POC killed by the virus is devastating.
